1
00:00:22,470 --> 00:00:25,301
[crowd clapping]

2
00:00:25,335 --> 00:00:29,374
[dramatic instrumental music]

3
00:00:48,289 --> 00:00:49,394
[puppy whimpering]

4
00:00:50,291 --> 00:00:52,362
- Naughty baby, whatever will you about?

5
00:00:53,432 --> 00:00:56,125
What if everyone should
run away from home?

6
00:00:56,159 --> 00:00:58,299
Why, there would be no more home at all.

7
00:00:58,334 --> 00:01:01,164
And then what should
your mommy do but cry?

8
00:01:01,199 --> 00:01:03,028
You don't want your mommy to cry.

9
00:01:03,063 --> 00:01:04,616
Do you?
- Elizabeth?

10
00:01:04,650 --> 00:01:05,996
Elizabeth, we're leaving.

11
00:01:06,031 --> 00:01:07,619
We're leaving now.

12
00:01:08,378 --> 00:01:10,691
- Come back, you naughty baby.

13
00:01:12,382 --> 00:01:15,351
- Oh yes, and if it were up to
you, we'd accomplish nothing.

14
00:01:15,385 --> 00:01:18,802
- Sarah, no one doubts
your drive for a moment.

15
00:01:18,837 --> 00:01:20,149
- Elizabeth.

16
00:01:20,183 --> 00:01:23,152
Elizabeth Taylor, are you
deliberately being naughty?

17
00:01:23,186 --> 00:01:24,670
- I merely question if it's natural

18
00:01:24,705 --> 00:01:26,224
to put a child out to work.

19
00:01:26,258 --> 00:01:27,777
- Oh, and you're such an expert

20
00:01:27,811 --> 00:01:29,848
on the natural order, Francis?

21
00:01:29,882 --> 00:01:33,541
Besides, I'm hardly sending
her off to the coal mines.

22
00:01:33,576 --> 00:01:36,303
To have a chance to be more than an--

23
00:01:36,337 --> 00:01:37,787
- Art dealer's wife?

24
00:01:37,821 --> 00:01:41,791
- Oh my, we're full of canny
wisdom this morning, aren't we?

25
00:01:41,825 --> 00:01:43,310
Get the bloody dogs.

26
00:01:44,380 --> 00:01:47,797
Elizabeth, tell Daddy
this is what you want.

27
00:01:47,831 --> 00:01:50,386
Tell him Mommy isn't
forcing you to do anything.

28
00:01:50,420 --> 00:01:53,872
Tell him you have always
dreamed of being a movie star.

29
00:01:53,906 --> 00:01:55,632
- But I haven't.

30
00:01:55,667 --> 00:01:56,530
- What?

31
00:01:59,326 --> 00:02:01,155
Is this your doing?

32
00:02:01,190 --> 00:02:03,261
- Bye, bye Elizabeth.

33
00:02:03,295 --> 00:02:04,296
- Bye, Daddy.

34
00:02:04,331 --> 00:02:06,781
I want to be an actress.

35
00:02:06,816 --> 00:02:09,922
Actresses can make
people believe anything.

36
00:02:09,957 --> 00:02:12,166
- Yes, well, actresses go hungry.

37
00:02:12,201 --> 00:02:14,720
I know, I saw enough of them when I tried

38
00:02:14,755 --> 00:02:16,550
for a career in the theater.

39
00:02:16,584 --> 00:02:17,551
Here you go.

40
00:02:18,690 --> 00:02:19,553
Hop in.

41
00:02:23,971 --> 00:02:26,698
But movie stars have everything.

42
00:02:31,392 --> 00:02:35,707
All right now, we mustn't
keep Aunt Hedda waiting.

43
00:02:36,570 --> 00:02:39,573
- Is Miss Hedda really my aunt, Mommy?

44
00:02:40,884 --> 00:02:45,372
- Hedda Hopper may well turn
out to be our fairy godmother.

45
00:02:46,511 --> 00:02:48,029
♪ Danube's so blue ♪

46
00:02:48,064 --> 00:02:50,411
♪ I'm longing for you ♪

47
00:02:50,446 --> 00:02:53,828
♪ My heart's ever true ♪

48
00:02:53,863 --> 00:02:54,795
♪ Today ♪

49
00:02:54,829 --> 00:02:55,623
- Sarah?

50
00:02:55,658 --> 00:02:59,179
Perhaps if she had some accompaniment.

51
00:02:59,213 --> 00:03:00,110
- I can't play.

52
00:03:00,145 --> 00:03:01,698
Perhaps you?

53
00:03:01,733 --> 00:03:02,803
- Oh god, no.

54
00:03:03,562 --> 00:03:05,357
That's just there for show,

55
00:03:05,392 --> 00:03:07,946
like everything else in this town.

56
00:03:07,980 --> 00:03:11,398
And Sarah, she is a lovely child, but...

57
00:03:12,571 --> 00:03:16,437
Elizabeth, the would is full
of things for you to do.

58
00:03:16,472 --> 00:03:19,233
You can marry, teach, be a nurse.

59
00:03:19,268 --> 00:03:23,099
You don't have to be an actress, you know.

60
00:03:23,133 --> 00:03:24,583
Not to be happy.

61
00:03:33,213 --> 00:03:34,283
- Aren't you a love?

62
00:03:34,317 --> 00:03:37,286
Aren't you Mummy's precious love.

63
00:03:38,045 --> 00:03:39,011
You're so pretty.

64
00:03:39,046 --> 00:03:40,806
- You know, Sarah.

65
00:03:40,841 --> 00:03:44,707
I might just have a
rabbit or two in my hat.

66
00:03:53,163 --> 00:03:55,235
- Okay Hedda, what'd I do wrong?

67
00:03:55,269 --> 00:03:58,307
- [laughing] Well don't
be such a goose, Sam.

68
00:03:58,341 --> 00:04:00,964
Oh, I do hope I'm interrupting.

69
00:04:00,999 --> 00:04:02,276
- You are.

70
00:04:02,311 --> 00:04:05,037
We're just about to cast
the little girl for Lassie.

71
00:04:05,072 --> 00:04:07,247
Stick around, you're gonna
have a scoop for your column.

72
00:04:07,281 --> 00:04:08,455
- Oh really?

73
00:04:10,353 --> 00:04:14,530
Well, Sam, you are about
to make a huge mistake.

74
00:04:15,841 --> 00:04:18,396
- None of them are above four feet, Hedda,

75
00:04:18,430 --> 00:04:19,638
it can't be that huge.

76
00:04:19,673 --> 00:04:22,676
- Well, if you had read
my column recently,

77
00:04:22,710 --> 00:04:26,300
you would know that
very dear family friends

78
00:04:26,335 --> 00:04:28,475
have just arrived from London,

79
00:04:28,509 --> 00:04:31,374
moments ahead of the blitz, as it were.

80
00:04:31,409 --> 00:04:34,584
- I'm sorry Hedda, we pretty
much made our decision.

81
00:04:34,619 --> 00:04:37,449
- Huh, you think you have.

82
00:04:37,484 --> 00:04:39,209
Elizabeth, Sam Marks,

83
00:04:39,244 --> 00:04:42,972
permit me to present,
Miss Elizabeth Taylor.

84
00:04:47,494 --> 00:04:50,531
- [chuckling] I know all
about this little lady.

85
00:04:50,566 --> 00:04:53,534
Her father Francis and I were
air raid wardens together.

86
00:04:53,569 --> 00:04:56,261
He told me his wife was dying
to see her in the movies,

87
00:04:56,296 --> 00:04:59,022
I told him I'd try and take a look at her.

88
00:04:59,057 --> 00:05:00,748
Elizabeth.

89
00:05:00,783 --> 00:05:01,646
- Yes sir?

90
00:05:03,441 --> 00:05:06,375
- Elizabeth, do you think you can act?

91
00:05:06,409 --> 00:05:07,893
- I have, many times.

92
00:05:07,928 --> 00:05:09,170
- Where was that?

93
00:05:09,205 --> 00:05:11,000
- A bit at Universal.

94
00:05:11,034 --> 00:05:13,036
There's One Born Every Minute?

95
00:05:13,071 --> 00:05:13,761
You must have seen it.

96
00:05:13,796 --> 00:05:14,866
- I don't think so.

97
00:05:14,900 --> 00:05:18,318
Elizabeth, do you think
you could talk to a dog

98
00:05:18,352 --> 00:05:21,666
and make us believe you believe it?

99
00:05:21,700 --> 00:05:23,599
- Could you wait a moment?

100
00:05:23,633 --> 00:05:24,496
- Sure.

101
00:05:38,614 --> 00:05:40,270
- I know you love me, Lassie,

102
00:05:40,305 --> 00:05:42,963
because no matter how far away you go,

103
00:05:42,997 --> 00:05:45,206
you'll always come back.

104
00:05:45,241 --> 00:05:46,207
You know why?

105
00:05:46,242 --> 00:05:48,002
Because you love me.

106
00:05:48,037 --> 00:05:51,316
You don't want your Mummy to cry.

107
00:05:51,351 --> 00:05:54,181
Do you know a secret, Lassie?

108
00:05:54,215 --> 00:05:57,115
If everyone ran away from home,

109
00:05:57,149 --> 00:05:59,600
there would be no more home.

110
00:06:03,949 --> 00:06:05,192
- Hedda.

111
00:06:05,226 --> 00:06:06,089
I owe you.

112
00:06:07,056 --> 00:06:07,919
- Uh huh.

113
00:06:13,890 --> 00:06:18,032
- Of all time, the
original Lassie stars in,

114
00:06:18,067 --> 00:06:19,586
Lassie Come Home.

115
00:06:21,104 --> 00:06:23,383
You must see the original Lassie

116
00:06:23,417 --> 00:06:27,387
in her greatest movie
role, Lassie Come Home.

117
00:06:28,595 --> 00:06:31,183
Introducing, Elizabeth Taylor.

118
00:06:33,254 --> 00:06:36,292
- Darling girl, you got wonderful reviews

119
00:06:36,326 --> 00:06:37,811
for your work in Lassie.

120
00:06:37,845 --> 00:06:40,469
I wrote one myself, remember?

121
00:06:40,503 --> 00:06:43,126
Why not rest a bit on your laurels?

122
00:06:43,161 --> 00:06:46,233
- But Aunt Hedda, it
truly is my favorite book.

123
00:06:46,267 --> 00:06:49,374
- Elizabeth, I think Mr. Mayer knows best.

124
00:06:49,409 --> 00:06:51,341
Besides, your plate is quite full

125
00:06:51,376 --> 00:06:53,067
with White Cliffs of Dover.

126
00:06:53,102 --> 00:06:54,552
Your time will come, dear.

127
00:06:54,586 --> 00:06:57,209
It has to, with Lassie
such a huge success.

128
00:06:57,244 --> 00:06:58,245
- It isn't fair.

129
00:06:58,279 --> 00:07:00,454
I was born to play Velvet Brown.

130
00:07:00,489 --> 00:07:01,593
I ride.

131
00:07:01,628 --> 00:07:02,456
I ride like a--

132
00:07:02,491 --> 00:07:03,906
- Listen to me, Elizabeth.

133
00:07:03,940 --> 00:07:07,116
You could turn yourself
into a flying horse

134
00:07:07,150 --> 00:07:11,051
and they still won't
give you National Velvet.

135
00:07:11,948 --> 00:07:15,849
They're looking for someone more mature.

136
00:07:15,883 --> 00:07:16,677
- Taller?

137
00:07:16,712 --> 00:07:19,024
- Well, taller, yes.

138
00:07:19,059 --> 00:07:21,441
But someone more developed.

139
00:07:22,165 --> 00:07:23,097
- You mean?

140
00:07:26,169 --> 00:07:28,758
- Uh, we'll stick with taller.

141
00:07:30,657 --> 00:07:33,798
[sentimental music]

142
00:07:58,201 --> 00:08:01,204
- National Velvet, scene 28, take 2.

143
00:08:11,214 --> 00:08:13,078
- Heels down, Elizabeth, heels down!

144
00:08:13,113 --> 00:08:16,047
- What a determined
young lady, Miss Taylor.

145
00:08:16,081 --> 00:08:20,500
Elizabeth has really
blossomed into Velvet Brown.

146
00:08:29,854 --> 00:08:30,786
[cries out]

147
00:08:30,820 --> 00:08:32,995
- Elizabeth!
- Cut!

148
00:08:33,029 --> 00:08:34,272
- Let's go, come on!

149
00:08:34,306 --> 00:08:35,376
- Are you all right?

150
00:08:35,411 --> 00:08:36,723
Is it your back?

151
00:08:36,757 --> 00:08:39,035
Get an ambulance, she's hurt her back!

152
00:08:39,070 --> 00:08:40,934
- No no, don't do that.

153
00:08:40,968 --> 00:08:41,935
I'm fine.

154
00:08:41,969 --> 00:08:43,108
Smashing.

155
00:08:43,143 --> 00:08:46,387
I ought to know to have kept
my heels down a bit more.

156
00:08:46,422 --> 00:08:49,598
- That was quite a tumble, kiddo.

157
00:08:49,632 --> 00:08:51,013
Let's call it a day.

158
00:08:51,047 --> 00:08:52,048
- No no, don't.

159
00:08:52,083 --> 00:08:52,739
I'll be fine.

160
00:08:52,773 --> 00:08:55,051
Just let me catch my breath.

161
00:08:55,086 --> 00:08:56,087
- You sure?

162
00:08:56,121 --> 00:08:56,984
- Yeah.

163
00:08:58,503 --> 00:08:59,953
- Darling.

164
00:08:59,987 --> 00:09:03,819
I know you think I push
too much, too hard,

165
00:09:04,578 --> 00:09:05,786
but even I don't expect.

166
00:09:05,821 --> 00:09:06,960
- Mummy.

167
00:09:06,994 --> 00:09:09,859
I know that at first I didn't
want to be a movie star,

168
00:09:09,894 --> 00:09:12,621
but now, now if I couldn't be in films,

169
00:09:12,655 --> 00:09:15,831
I'd feel like a tree that fell down.

170
00:09:16,728 --> 00:09:19,075
A tree without roots.

171
00:09:19,110 --> 00:09:20,698
Isn't he wondrous?

172
00:09:24,253 --> 00:09:26,669
I loved him at first sight.

173
00:09:26,704 --> 00:09:31,191
Do you think they'd give
him to me after the film?

174
00:09:31,225 --> 00:09:32,951
- Darling, after this film,

175
00:09:32,986 --> 00:09:36,092
I imagine they'd give you anything.

176
00:09:38,025 --> 00:09:41,788
- A sweeping saga of love,
tenderness and courage.

177
00:09:41,822 --> 00:09:44,894
You'll thrill to the new screen sensation,

178
00:09:44,929 --> 00:09:48,449
Elizabeth Taylor, as she
steals your heart in,

179
00:09:48,484 --> 00:09:52,799
National Velvet.
[dramatic music]

180
00:10:10,299 --> 00:10:11,576
- Bye, darling.

181
00:10:11,611 --> 00:10:12,888
- Janie?

182
00:10:12,922 --> 00:10:15,856
Why don't you continue with
your essay on Wordsworth

183
00:10:15,891 --> 00:10:17,962
that you started last week.

184
00:10:17,996 --> 00:10:19,273
Dickie, Darrell.

185
00:10:20,620 --> 00:10:22,035
- More like last month.

186
00:10:22,069 --> 00:10:25,555
I've been writing the same
essay through my last two films.

187
00:10:25,590 --> 00:10:26,487
- Oh, children!

188
00:10:26,522 --> 00:10:27,419
I'm afraid you'll have to forgo

189
00:10:27,454 --> 00:10:28,904
your science test until tomorrow.

190
00:10:28,938 --> 00:10:31,251
Mr. Strickland of
publicity wants to come in

191
00:10:31,285 --> 00:10:34,599
and make a few suggestions
before you meet with photo play.

192
00:10:34,634 --> 00:10:35,565
- Night shoot?

193
00:10:35,600 --> 00:10:36,946
- Three in a row.

194
00:10:36,981 --> 00:10:39,811
Been up at the bloody crack
of dawn to study my lines.

195
00:10:39,846 --> 00:10:41,226
- It's worth it, though.

196
00:10:41,261 --> 00:10:45,161
Everyone says National
Velvet will make you a star.

197
00:10:45,196 --> 00:10:46,991
- I'm already a star.

198
00:10:49,890 --> 00:10:52,652
- Three, two.
[bright music]

199
00:10:52,686 --> 00:10:54,343
- This is Hedda Hopper.

200
00:10:54,377 --> 00:10:56,759
And this is Hollywood.

201
00:10:56,794 --> 00:10:59,831
Elizabeth Taylor is in New
York to be photographed

202
00:10:59,866 --> 00:11:02,834
for her 17th birthday
spread in Life Magazine

203
00:11:02,869 --> 00:11:04,456
by Felipe Hoffman.

204
00:11:06,735 --> 00:11:07,805
- It's rather scary.

205
00:11:07,839 --> 00:11:10,014
I mean, Life Magazine.

206
00:11:10,048 --> 00:11:13,224
- It's your birthday spread in Life.

207
00:11:18,816 --> 00:11:20,887
I think it's time the studio realized

208
00:11:20,921 --> 00:11:24,166
that their baby girl is all grown up.

209
00:11:25,926 --> 00:11:26,996
- At 17?

210
00:11:27,031 --> 00:11:27,894
- 17?

211
00:11:28,757 --> 00:11:29,792
Famous.

212
00:11:32,415 --> 00:11:34,383
You're uncomfortable?

213
00:11:34,417 --> 00:11:35,280
- No.

214
00:11:38,387 --> 00:11:39,526
Maybe.

215
00:11:39,560 --> 00:11:40,872
- Know why?

216
00:11:40,907 --> 00:11:44,427
Because I am focusing on your whole body.

217
00:11:48,742 --> 00:11:50,710
It is a woman's body.

218
00:11:53,436 --> 00:11:54,299
Stunning.

219
00:11:55,611 --> 00:11:57,440
Like a woman.

220
00:11:57,475 --> 00:11:59,097
Free, like a woman.

221
00:11:59,132 --> 00:11:59,995
Sensuous.

222
00:12:01,272 --> 00:12:02,825
- I don't know.

223
00:12:02,860 --> 00:12:04,793
Inside I still feel like a girl.

224
00:12:04,827 --> 00:12:06,829
- But you're not a little girl.

225
00:12:06,864 --> 00:12:09,142
You are a woman.

226
00:12:09,176 --> 00:12:10,039
Yes, yes.

227
00:12:12,904 --> 00:12:13,767
You have bosoms.

228
00:12:13,802 --> 00:12:15,389
So stick them out!

229
00:12:16,494 --> 00:12:19,290
[romantic music]

230
00:12:32,752 --> 00:12:33,718
- Well.

231
00:12:33,753 --> 00:12:36,617
There's your Mr. Montgomery Clift.

232
00:12:36,652 --> 00:12:39,517
- He's beautiful, isn't he, Mummy?

233
00:12:41,622 --> 00:12:43,003
- Go say hello.

234
00:13:00,641 --> 00:13:01,504
- Coffee?

235
00:13:08,580 --> 00:13:10,444
Don't do that.

236
00:13:10,479 --> 00:13:11,756
- Do what?

237
00:13:11,791 --> 00:13:13,102
- Stare at me.

238
00:13:13,447 --> 00:13:14,448
- Oh.

239
00:13:14,483 --> 00:13:17,210
Me too, I'm so tired
of people staring at me

240
00:13:17,244 --> 00:13:19,281
and telling me I'm beautiful.

241
00:13:19,315 --> 00:13:19,971
I hate it.

242
00:13:20,006 --> 00:13:21,628
- Well you are beautiful.

243
00:13:21,662 --> 00:13:23,492
And it says so right here.

244
00:13:23,526 --> 00:13:24,700
And I'm beautiful.

245
00:13:24,734 --> 00:13:28,152
This is the movies, even the
ugly people are beautiful.

246
00:13:28,186 --> 00:13:29,049
So what?

247
00:13:30,533 --> 00:13:32,432
- I'm Elizabeth Taylor.

248
00:13:37,851 --> 00:13:40,371
- Monty Clift, how do you do?

249
00:13:42,787 --> 00:13:47,136
Listen, you know what
the word is around here?

250
00:13:47,171 --> 00:13:49,898
You're the girl on the candy box cover.

251
00:13:49,932 --> 00:13:51,382
Is that what you want?

252
00:13:51,416 --> 00:13:53,004
To be a thing?

253
00:13:53,039 --> 00:13:55,558
Because I have to be honest
with you, Bessie Mae.

254
00:13:55,593 --> 00:13:58,216
I don't do my best work
against a mannequin.

255
00:13:58,251 --> 00:14:00,598
- Well then you'd better help
me, mister method acting,

256
00:14:00,632 --> 00:14:05,637
because I've done my finest
work opposite a horse and a dog.

257
00:14:05,672 --> 00:14:07,570
[barking]

258
00:14:07,605 --> 00:14:10,608
[laughing] Stop it!

259
00:14:11,643 --> 00:14:12,472
- Uh oh.

260
00:14:12,506 --> 00:14:13,335
Oh, dear.

261
00:14:13,369 --> 00:14:14,060
- What's wrong?

262
00:14:14,094 --> 00:14:15,613
Are you all right?

263
00:14:15,647 --> 00:14:16,717
- Dog biscuits.

264
00:14:16,752 --> 00:14:18,547
For the shakes.

265
00:14:18,581 --> 00:14:20,066
Great method actor, huh?

266
00:14:20,100 --> 00:14:22,827
Still getting stage fright.

267
00:14:22,862 --> 00:14:23,932
- Pain pills.

268
00:14:23,966 --> 00:14:25,105
For my back.

269
00:14:25,899 --> 00:14:28,143
Came courtesy of National Velvet.

270
00:14:28,177 --> 00:14:31,215
- Oh, we're a sorry pair, Bessie Mae.

271
00:14:31,249 --> 00:14:32,319
A sorry pair.

272
00:14:33,769 --> 00:14:34,804
- Bessie Mae.

273
00:14:34,839 --> 00:14:37,117
[laughing]

274
00:14:37,152 --> 00:14:39,188
Monty look at you, you're so thin.

275
00:14:39,223 --> 00:14:41,087
Come, let's eat something.

276
00:14:41,121 --> 00:14:42,571
- Oh dammit, I'm not hungry.

277
00:14:42,605 --> 00:14:46,299
- Oh come on, you look as if
you never eat, and you have to.

278
00:14:46,333 --> 00:14:47,921
You can't live on.

279
00:14:48,888 --> 00:14:51,131
Go on then, do it for me.

280
00:14:52,719 --> 00:14:54,100
Do it for Mama.

281
00:14:55,722 --> 00:14:57,103
Do it for Mama.

282
00:15:03,730 --> 00:15:06,112
[laughing]

283
00:15:11,289 --> 00:15:14,948
- Oh, good grief, I got the
same hand I got last time.

284
00:15:14,983 --> 00:15:15,949
- I bet a dime.

285
00:15:15,984 --> 00:15:17,019
- Me too.

286
00:15:19,159 --> 00:15:20,126
- Come on, Elizabeth.

287
00:15:20,160 --> 00:15:22,922
- Rewrites for the next scene.

288
00:15:27,098 --> 00:15:31,516
- Excuse me George, but
what the hell is this?

289
00:15:31,551 --> 00:15:33,415
This is, this is ridiculous!

290
00:15:33,449 --> 00:15:37,695
No young lady would speak
this way to the man she loves.

291
00:15:37,729 --> 00:15:38,661
- She will.

292
00:15:39,835 --> 00:15:41,043
- Potato face.

293
00:15:41,078 --> 00:15:45,254
- Elizabeth, will you pay
attention to the game.

294
00:15:46,221 --> 00:15:49,983
[sweeping romantic music]

295
00:15:54,470 --> 00:15:56,679
- I'm the happiest person in the world.

296
00:15:56,714 --> 00:15:58,129
- Second happiest.

297
00:15:58,164 --> 00:16:01,546
- Oh Angela, if only I could
tell you how much I love you.

298
00:16:01,581 --> 00:16:03,031
If only I could tell all.

299
00:16:03,065 --> 00:16:04,170
- Tell 'em.

300
00:16:04,964 --> 00:16:06,206
Tell 'em all.

301
00:16:22,326 --> 00:16:23,258
- And, cut.

302
00:16:23,983 --> 00:16:27,227
Print.
[bell ringing]

303
00:16:38,859 --> 00:16:40,240
I was right, wasn't I?

304
00:16:40,275 --> 00:16:42,208
About that new line.

305
00:16:42,242 --> 00:16:43,588
- Don't be ridiculous.

306
00:16:43,623 --> 00:16:47,765
No woman wants to be Mama
to the many she loves.

307
00:17:02,745 --> 00:17:05,334
[dog barking]

308
00:17:14,033 --> 00:17:16,449
- Why don't you take the day off work?

309
00:17:16,483 --> 00:17:21,074
We could drive down to
the beach or something.

310
00:17:21,109 --> 00:17:23,697
- Knock knock, I come bearing gifts!

311
00:17:23,732 --> 00:17:25,527
- Well hello Bessie Mae!

312
00:17:25,561 --> 00:17:26,838
What a lifesaver.

313
00:17:26,873 --> 00:17:28,081
Uh, give me a minute Billy

314
00:17:28,116 --> 00:17:30,118
and we'll go for our little drive, okay?

315
00:17:30,152 --> 00:17:32,706
- Right, I'll see you later.

316
00:17:32,741 --> 00:17:34,536
- I'm sorry, I'm interrupting.

317
00:17:34,570 --> 00:17:36,365
- No no no, no no no.

318
00:17:38,850 --> 00:17:40,128
Now you hate me.

319
00:17:40,162 --> 00:17:41,094
- Hate you?

320
00:17:41,129 --> 00:17:43,372
My God Monty, I love you.

321
00:17:45,512 --> 00:17:46,824
- I know.

322
00:17:46,858 --> 00:17:47,721
I know.

323
00:17:48,998 --> 00:17:50,931
- I have since that first day

324
00:17:50,966 --> 00:17:53,624
when you refused to speak to my breasts.

325
00:17:53,658 --> 00:17:58,042
- Well Bessie Mae, let me
now address your breasts.

326
00:17:58,077 --> 00:18:00,286
- [laughing] Stop it.

327
00:18:00,320 --> 00:18:02,736
- Don't give me so much credit.

328
00:18:02,771 --> 00:18:04,152
- Oh, damn you.

329
00:18:04,186 --> 00:18:05,808
You've broken my heart.

330
00:18:05,843 --> 00:18:06,671
- I know.

331
00:18:06,706 --> 00:18:08,777
Hell, I've broken my own.

332
00:18:12,470 --> 00:18:14,472
You're the girl, Bessie Mae.

333
00:18:14,507 --> 00:18:18,821
If anyone could have lured me
away from my wicked loving.

334
00:18:21,652 --> 00:18:23,240
- It doesn't matter.

335
00:18:23,274 --> 00:18:27,451
Whatever happens, I will
always be here for you.

336
00:18:33,836 --> 00:18:36,632
Mama will always be here for you.

337
00:18:40,636 --> 00:18:43,639
[bright jazz music]

338
00:18:57,481 --> 00:19:00,208
- Aren't you ever gonna dance?

339
00:19:00,242 --> 00:19:01,209
- I suppose.

340
00:19:01,243 --> 00:19:02,900
- It's Monty, right?

341
00:19:02,934 --> 00:19:04,212
- Oh, that is so silly,

342
00:19:04,246 --> 00:19:06,559
just because I want to be
alone with my thoughts.

343
00:19:06,593 --> 00:19:09,424
- You are still in love with that guy.

344
00:19:09,458 --> 00:19:12,254
- Monty and I have great
respect for each other.

345
00:19:12,289 --> 00:19:14,670
He understands the nature of me.

346
00:19:14,705 --> 00:19:16,155
- Excuse me?

347
00:19:16,189 --> 00:19:18,053
Ever since A Place In The Sun,

348
00:19:18,087 --> 00:19:20,918
you have become queen of the world.

349
00:19:20,952 --> 00:19:24,266
- You know, Debbie, it's like
your souls meet somewhere else

350
00:19:24,301 --> 00:19:25,509
and they come here.

351
00:19:25,543 --> 00:19:27,442
And if they don't meet again,

352
00:19:27,476 --> 00:19:31,756
then you spend your whole life
like a wanderer, searching.

353
00:19:31,791 --> 00:19:32,999
- Jeepers.

354
00:19:33,033 --> 00:19:34,242
- Jeepers?

355
00:19:34,276 --> 00:19:36,520
I tell you something as
deeply moving as that,

356
00:19:36,554 --> 00:19:39,385
and you answer me like a teenager!

357
00:19:39,419 --> 00:19:40,972
- I am a teenager!

358
00:19:41,007 --> 00:19:42,560
And so are you.

359
00:19:42,595 --> 00:19:46,288
- [sighs] Will no one
treat me like a grownup?

360
00:19:46,323 --> 00:19:48,014
- Well that handsome hunk over there

361
00:19:48,048 --> 00:19:51,362
seems to think you've grown up enough.

362
00:19:53,192 --> 00:19:55,055
- Who is that?

363
00:19:55,090 --> 00:19:55,953
- Nicky Hilton.

364
00:19:55,987 --> 00:19:57,126
- Who?

365
00:19:57,161 --> 00:19:58,852
- His parents only own
the Waldorf Astoria,

366
00:19:58,887 --> 00:20:01,061
and about a hundred other hotels.

367
00:20:01,096 --> 00:20:01,959
- Hmm.

368
00:20:05,100 --> 00:20:06,584
He's coming this way.

369
00:20:06,619 --> 00:20:07,620
Say something.

370
00:20:07,654 --> 00:20:09,069
- [squeals] Broccoli broccoli!

371
00:20:09,104 --> 00:20:10,726
- Stop it, Debbie. [laughing]

372
00:20:10,761 --> 00:20:11,762
- Excuse me.

373
00:20:11,796 --> 00:20:14,730
You don't know who I am,
but you're Liz Taylor.

374
00:20:14,765 --> 00:20:15,973
- Oh, I hate that name.

375
00:20:16,007 --> 00:20:17,112
- Liz, or Taylor?

376
00:20:17,146 --> 00:20:18,631
I can change one of them.

377
00:20:18,665 --> 00:20:19,183
- Liz.

378
00:20:19,218 --> 00:20:20,529
- I'm Nicky Hilton.

379
00:20:20,564 --> 00:20:22,497
- And this is a close friend
of mine, Debbie Reynolds.

380
00:20:22,531 --> 00:20:23,843
- Debbie.

381
00:20:23,877 --> 00:20:25,224
As her close friend,

382
00:20:25,258 --> 00:20:27,778
do you think Elizabeth
should dance with me?

383
00:20:27,812 --> 00:20:30,194
- I'm always telling Elizabeth what to do,

384
00:20:30,229 --> 00:20:32,300
and she never listens. [laughing]

385
00:20:32,334 --> 00:20:34,129
- Okay wiseguy, what should I do?

386
00:20:34,163 --> 00:20:35,889
- Go dance with him.

387
00:20:37,822 --> 00:20:40,687
[slow jazz music]

388
00:21:01,605 --> 00:21:05,298
- Test for picture number
17271, Father Of The Bride,

389
00:21:05,333 --> 00:21:09,889
director Vincent Minelli,
actor Elizabeth Taylor.

390
00:21:09,923 --> 00:21:10,890
- Turn, please.

391
00:21:10,924 --> 00:21:11,891
Turn right.

392
00:21:11,925 --> 00:21:12,788
And left.

393
00:21:18,035 --> 00:21:20,106
- It's crazy, I know, so sudden.

394
00:21:20,140 --> 00:21:24,317
But if I mean to escape
I've got only two options.

395
00:21:24,352 --> 00:21:25,905
College, or marriage.

396
00:21:25,939 --> 00:21:29,115
And with everyone making
my decisions for me,

397
00:21:29,149 --> 00:21:31,531
I can't even pee without instructions.

398
00:21:31,566 --> 00:21:34,465
- Uh oh, Bessie Mae, sound
like you're going method on me,

399
00:21:34,500 --> 00:21:36,571
what with a the Father
Of The Bride and all.

400
00:21:36,605 --> 00:21:38,952
- [laughing] Be serious.

401
00:21:38,987 --> 00:21:40,402
- Okay.

402
00:21:40,437 --> 00:21:42,404
Do you love this guy?

403
00:21:44,268 --> 00:21:45,787
- Would you mind?

404
00:21:47,616 --> 00:21:51,931
- [sighs] I just want you
to be happy, that's all.

405
00:21:52,863 --> 00:21:54,796
You be careful, though.

406
00:21:55,797 --> 00:21:57,350
Whatever you decide,

407
00:21:57,385 --> 00:21:58,903
I heard a few things.

408
00:22:00,042 --> 00:22:03,977
- You mean he's not an
actor or a suffering poet.

409
00:22:04,012 --> 00:22:04,978
[laughing]

410
00:22:05,013 --> 00:22:07,153
I do believe you're jealous.

411
00:22:07,187 --> 00:22:08,844
- Okay, maybe I am.

412
00:22:09,776 --> 00:22:10,846
- Well, good.

413
00:22:12,710 --> 00:22:14,919
[cheering]

414
00:22:28,933 --> 00:22:30,245
- What's next, Liz?

415
00:22:30,279 --> 00:22:32,661
- Well I want nothing more than
to spend the rest of my life

416
00:22:32,696 --> 00:22:36,078
as Mrs. Conrad Nicholson Hilton Junior.

417
00:22:47,400 --> 00:22:48,367
- Oh good evening.

418
00:22:48,401 --> 00:22:50,576
Hasn't it been a lovely day?

419
00:22:50,610 --> 00:22:53,026
Do please follow me.

420
00:22:55,581 --> 00:22:57,376
Miss Taylor, this is your table.

421
00:22:57,410 --> 00:22:58,722
- Wrong, pal.

422
00:22:58,756 --> 00:23:02,242
We're looking for the table
of Mr. and Mrs. Hilton.

423
00:23:02,277 --> 00:23:05,004
- Oh Mr. Hilton, I do apologize.

424
00:23:05,038 --> 00:23:07,696
This of course is your table.

425
00:23:07,731 --> 00:23:08,732
- Thank you.

426
00:23:11,010 --> 00:23:12,149
- Bon appetit.

427
00:23:13,978 --> 00:23:14,979
- Husband.

428
00:23:15,014 --> 00:23:19,363
I've only been able to
stay that for a week.

429
00:23:19,398 --> 00:23:21,710
Husband, husband, husband.

430
00:23:23,781 --> 00:23:26,439
Promise you'll love me forever.

431
00:23:26,474 --> 00:23:28,752
No, more than forever.

432
00:23:28,786 --> 00:23:29,649
- Fine.

433
00:23:30,995 --> 00:23:34,378
- If you were an actor, I'd
make you work on that reading.

434
00:23:34,413 --> 00:23:36,345
- Well I'm not an actor, okay?

435
00:23:36,380 --> 00:23:37,623
You got that?

436
00:23:42,559 --> 00:23:44,492
- Oh please, this is my honeymoon.

437
00:23:44,526 --> 00:23:46,148
- Oh please, just one.

438
00:23:46,183 --> 00:23:47,495
- Yes, please.

439
00:23:53,190 --> 00:23:54,778
- Are you famous too?

440
00:23:54,812 --> 00:23:57,919
- Not to old bats like you I'm not.

441
00:23:58,920 --> 00:24:00,577
- The nerve of him.

442
00:24:04,304 --> 00:24:05,167
Thank you.

443
00:24:09,137 --> 00:24:11,208
- This is my honeymoon.

444
00:24:11,242 --> 00:24:12,209
- Mine too.

445
00:24:12,243 --> 00:24:14,038
- Don't embarrass me.

446
00:24:14,901 --> 00:24:15,592
- Waiter.

447
00:24:15,626 --> 00:24:18,215
Bring us a fifth of something.

448
00:24:19,078 --> 00:24:19,941
Gin!

449
00:24:30,192 --> 00:24:31,021
And raise.

450
00:24:42,066 --> 00:24:43,861
- Three threes, fold.

451
00:24:46,312 --> 00:24:49,626
[wistful piano music]

452
00:25:18,965 --> 00:25:21,554
[glass breaking]

453
00:25:21,589 --> 00:25:22,486
- Nicky, honey?

454
00:25:22,521 --> 00:25:24,177
That you?

455
00:25:24,212 --> 00:25:25,075
- Yeah.

456
00:25:30,598 --> 00:25:32,323
- Are you all right?

457
00:25:33,566 --> 00:25:34,602
- Yeah.

458
00:25:44,543 --> 00:25:45,578
- Win big?

459
00:25:46,475 --> 00:25:47,269
- Yeah.

460
00:25:48,339 --> 00:25:50,583
Don't ever pull that Hollywood star crap

461
00:25:50,618 --> 00:25:52,930
with me again, you bitch.

462
00:25:52,965 --> 00:25:55,692
[cries in pain]

463
00:26:04,424 --> 00:26:07,600
- There were many violent outbursts.

464
00:26:11,155 --> 00:26:13,226
He was indifferent to me.

465
00:26:15,919 --> 00:26:20,544
- I'm sorry Mrs. Hilton,
we just can't hear you.

466
00:26:20,579 --> 00:26:22,960
- He was indifferent to me.

467
00:26:24,065 --> 00:26:27,102
It caused me great mental anguish.

468
00:26:28,863 --> 00:26:32,314
- I understand that you have
substantial income of your own

469
00:26:32,349 --> 00:26:34,109
and you wish to waive any alimony,

470
00:26:34,144 --> 00:26:38,148
and that you petition for the
right to use your maiden name.

471
00:26:38,182 --> 00:26:39,218
- Yes.

472
00:26:39,252 --> 00:26:43,015
- Divorce granted, this
marriage is dissolved.

473
00:26:43,049 --> 00:26:45,914
[people shouting]

474
00:26:48,917 --> 00:26:51,264
- Miss Taylor, what's next for you?

475
00:26:51,299 --> 00:26:53,922
- How do you feel, Miss Taylor?

476
00:27:09,317 --> 00:27:10,559
- I've let myself in.

477
00:27:10,594 --> 00:27:12,458
- Mother, this is my place.

478
00:27:12,492 --> 00:27:15,185
- Well, shall I go back out to knock?

479
00:27:15,219 --> 00:27:17,290
What's that your cooking?

480
00:27:17,325 --> 00:27:19,430
French toast for lunch?

481
00:27:19,465 --> 00:27:21,536
Well I won't say a word.

482
00:27:21,570 --> 00:27:23,124
Isn't this nice?

483
00:27:23,158 --> 00:27:24,677
Your own place.

484
00:27:24,712 --> 00:27:27,197
My little girl, all grown up.

485
00:27:27,231 --> 00:27:30,787
You know, we haven't said
a thing about Ivanhoe yet.

486
00:27:30,821 --> 00:27:34,687
- [sighs] I am committed,
but it's a terrible script.

487
00:27:34,722 --> 00:27:37,759
- Well that may well be,
but a few months in London,

488
00:27:37,794 --> 00:27:39,381
away from all the press,

489
00:27:39,416 --> 00:27:40,969
help them forget about your marriage.

490
00:27:41,004 --> 00:27:41,832
- Mummy.

491
00:27:41,867 --> 00:27:43,696
- Darling, clean up that egg, will you?

492
00:27:43,731 --> 00:27:44,732
It's dripping.

493
00:27:44,766 --> 00:27:47,079
- Mummy, have you spoken with Ben Thau?

494
00:27:47,113 --> 00:27:48,494
- About what?

495
00:27:48,528 --> 00:27:50,082
- About London.

496
00:27:50,116 --> 00:27:52,222
- [laughing] Well I know
all about London darling,

497
00:27:52,256 --> 00:27:54,362
we used to live there.

498
00:27:54,396 --> 00:27:58,815
- About how I won't be
needing a chaperone there.

499
00:27:59,539 --> 00:28:01,990
- This was Mr. Thau's idea?

500
00:28:02,025 --> 00:28:03,474
- And even though you'll be staying,

501
00:28:03,509 --> 00:28:05,304
you'll still be on salary.

502
00:28:05,338 --> 00:28:06,719
Benny promised.

503
00:28:08,100 --> 00:28:09,549
- I see.

504
00:28:09,584 --> 00:28:12,449
- I'm sorry, but it's as you said.

505
00:28:13,381 --> 00:28:14,900
I'm all grown up.

506
00:28:16,867 --> 00:28:19,249
- You're burning the toast.

507
00:28:20,837 --> 00:28:22,079
- All right, turn over.

508
00:28:22,114 --> 00:28:23,253
Camera rolling.

509
00:28:23,287 --> 00:28:23,943
Speed.

510
00:28:23,978 --> 00:28:25,531
Ivanhoe 72, marker.

511
00:28:25,565 --> 00:28:26,532
[board clapping]

512
00:28:26,566 --> 00:28:27,740
And, action.

513
00:28:28,603 --> 00:28:31,917
- That is the way it must be, Rebecca.

514
00:28:35,506 --> 00:28:37,888
That is the way it must be.

515
00:28:39,269 --> 00:28:40,339
Take it again.

516
00:28:40,373 --> 00:28:42,893
- But I don't understand why.

517
00:28:42,928 --> 00:28:45,378
- It is the law of the land.

518
00:28:49,244 --> 00:28:50,142
- And cut.

519
00:28:50,176 --> 00:28:51,971
Is there some problem, Elizabeth?

520
00:28:52,006 --> 00:28:53,973
- Yes, this headpiece weighs a ton.

521
00:28:54,008 --> 00:28:55,595
It's killing my poor back.

522
00:28:55,630 --> 00:28:57,183
- Well I'm more concerned about dialogue.

523
00:28:57,218 --> 00:28:58,737
Can we put a little life into it?

524
00:28:58,771 --> 00:29:00,911
- You should have told that to the writer.

525
00:29:00,946 --> 00:29:01,809
- Sir Walter Scott?

526
00:29:01,843 --> 00:29:02,810
He's dead.

527
00:29:02,844 --> 00:29:03,914
- You're telling me.

528
00:29:03,949 --> 00:29:05,744
- Well, if it isn't Michael Wilding,

529
00:29:05,778 --> 00:29:07,849
England's answer to Robert Taylor.

530
00:29:07,884 --> 00:29:09,989
- I could never aspire to
fill your chain mail, Robert.

531
00:29:10,024 --> 00:29:11,611
- [laughing] Well, slumming, Michael?

532
00:29:11,646 --> 00:29:14,891
Or have you rediscovered a
passion for Sir Walter Scott.

533
00:29:14,925 --> 00:29:16,478
- As a matter of fact,
I've become all curious

534
00:29:16,513 --> 00:29:18,964
about the ways and habits
of Hollywood starlets.

535
00:29:18,998 --> 00:29:21,069
- Well, this one's having a fit.

536
00:29:21,104 --> 00:29:24,417
- Quite fantastic, just
like a storm at sea.

537
00:29:24,452 --> 00:29:26,074
Don't care how many ships go down,

538
00:29:26,109 --> 00:29:28,076
just as long as we can watch them.

539
00:29:28,111 --> 00:29:30,320
[laughing]

540
00:29:33,047 --> 00:29:35,774
- Am I allowed to meet your friend?

541
00:29:35,808 --> 00:29:37,430
- This is Michael Wilding.

542
00:29:37,465 --> 00:29:39,329
Michael, this is Elizabeth Taylor.

543
00:29:39,363 --> 00:29:40,226
- Hello.

544
00:29:46,750 --> 00:29:48,959
[bell ringing]

545
00:29:48,994 --> 00:29:52,169
[sentimental music]

546
00:29:59,245 --> 00:30:02,076
- My dear, you look enchanting.

547
00:30:03,836 --> 00:30:04,872
Please.

548
00:30:07,875 --> 00:30:09,808
- Can you believe this is the first night

549
00:30:09,842 --> 00:30:11,395
I've been out on the town?

550
00:30:11,430 --> 00:30:12,396
- You know, I don't.

551
00:30:12,431 --> 00:30:13,328
A beauty like you.

552
00:30:13,363 --> 00:30:14,951
- Strange, everyone takes for granted

553
00:30:14,985 --> 00:30:18,471
that I have a date every night,
and nobody thinks to ask.

554
00:30:18,506 --> 00:30:19,921
- Oh, so I'm Mr. Nobody?

555
00:30:19,956 --> 00:30:22,372
- [laughing] You are funny.

556
00:30:22,406 --> 00:30:23,545
- For an older man?

557
00:30:23,580 --> 00:30:25,444
- Stop that, my father's an older man.

558
00:30:25,478 --> 00:30:28,205
- Are you quite sure
you wanted to say that?

559
00:30:28,240 --> 00:30:30,345
[laughing]

560
00:30:30,380 --> 00:30:31,519
- I like older men.

561
00:30:31,553 --> 00:30:36,213
They're wise about things
like, you know, life, love.

562
00:30:36,248 --> 00:30:39,251
- I'm not sure anyone's really that wise.

563
00:30:39,285 --> 00:30:40,286
Not about love.

564
00:30:40,321 --> 00:30:42,910
The poets claim it, but I don't think

565
00:30:42,944 --> 00:30:45,913
they really know what
they're complaining about.

566
00:30:45,947 --> 00:30:49,330
- God, if you couldn't believe in love.

567
00:30:50,849 --> 00:30:52,609
- Do you believe in love?

568
00:30:52,643 --> 00:30:54,266
- I used to.

569
00:30:54,300 --> 00:30:58,339
Used to be the most
important thing in my life.

570
00:30:58,373 --> 00:31:00,272
- I'm terribly sorry.

571
00:31:00,306 --> 00:31:05,277
- I'll bet you'd marry me if
I were older, wouldn't you?

572
00:31:05,311 --> 00:31:06,312
- I tell you what.

573
00:31:06,347 --> 00:31:10,247
You stay the same age,
and I'll get younger.

574
00:31:27,195 --> 00:31:30,164
- Elizabeth, please, no
thanks are necessary.

575
00:31:30,198 --> 00:31:32,683
We've always been a family here at Metro.

576
00:31:32,718 --> 00:31:34,685
Beside the, Michael's a great actor.

577
00:31:34,720 --> 00:31:37,343
We'd be more than happy
to put him under contract.

578
00:31:37,378 --> 00:31:40,484
- Oh, it'd be such a
help to us, thank you.

579
00:31:40,519 --> 00:31:41,347
- Good.

580
00:31:41,382 --> 00:31:42,383
- Also, a loan.

581
00:31:42,417 --> 00:31:44,868
We would love to get a house, a big house.

582
00:31:44,903 --> 00:31:47,353
We're so eager to start
a family, you know.

583
00:31:47,388 --> 00:31:49,942
And have dozens of children. [laughing]

584
00:31:49,977 --> 00:31:51,633
- Well yes, but not too soon.

585
00:31:51,668 --> 00:31:55,948
Elizabeth, we have big
plans for you, you know.

586
00:31:56,845 --> 00:31:58,157
[laughing]

587
00:31:58,192 --> 00:32:00,366
- You are certifiable, you know that?

588
00:32:00,401 --> 00:32:02,403
- Michaelangelo had the
roof of the Sistine.

589
00:32:02,437 --> 00:32:04,336
I make due with only slightly less space.

590
00:32:04,370 --> 00:32:05,993
- Bugger off, you British weasel.

591
00:32:06,027 --> 00:32:08,133
- You're as big as a
barn and mad as a hatter

592
00:32:08,167 --> 00:32:10,929
and I love you and I want you.

593
00:32:11,895 --> 00:32:13,966
- Don't forget to sign.

594
00:32:15,347 --> 00:32:17,556
[laughing]

595
00:32:34,366 --> 00:32:35,436
- Oh, Elizabeth.

596
00:32:35,470 --> 00:32:38,680
You won't believe this
script the studio sent me,

597
00:32:38,715 --> 00:32:41,304
it's nonsense, utter nonsense.

598
00:32:41,338 --> 00:32:44,583
- What is this, the third,
fourth script you've rejected?

599
00:32:44,617 --> 00:32:47,586
No pay, no play, Michael,
read the fine print.

600
00:32:47,620 --> 00:32:50,727
- You'd think they'd send
me anything top drawer.

601
00:32:50,761 --> 00:32:53,764
I mean, a man does have his dignity.

602
00:32:55,352 --> 00:32:58,252
- Dignity doesn't pay the bills, I do.

603
00:32:58,286 --> 00:33:00,771
I've done four dreadful
films back to back,

604
00:33:00,806 --> 00:33:04,672
and to be perfectly honest
with you, I feel as...

605
00:33:04,706 --> 00:33:07,295
I feel as though I'm drowning.

606
00:33:15,717 --> 00:33:20,205
A bit of help from the home
front wouldn't be amiss.

607
00:33:29,593 --> 00:33:30,422
- And cut!

608
00:33:30,456 --> 00:33:31,216
[whistling]

609
00:33:31,250 --> 00:33:32,079
Print.

610
00:33:32,113 --> 00:33:35,496
Get this over to the production office.

611
00:33:36,635 --> 00:33:39,638
- Hey dollface, you made it.

612
00:33:39,672 --> 00:33:41,053
You meet Jimmy?

613
00:33:42,192 --> 00:33:43,573
- Hello, Jimmy!

614
00:33:45,368 --> 00:33:46,990
Is he always like that?

615
00:33:47,025 --> 00:33:49,268
- No, sometimes he's just rude.

616
00:33:49,303 --> 00:33:50,925
Hey George, look who's here.

617
00:33:50,959 --> 00:33:52,202
- Hello Mama.

618
00:33:52,237 --> 00:33:53,514
- Hello potato face.

619
00:33:53,548 --> 00:33:56,034
- That's right dollface,
you show him who's boss.

620
00:33:56,068 --> 00:33:57,242
- You know why you're here?

621
00:33:57,276 --> 00:33:59,382
Because I told old George
I wanted Liz Taylor

622
00:33:59,416 --> 00:34:00,866
or I wouldn't do this damn thing.

623
00:34:00,900 --> 00:34:02,178
What do you think of that?

624
00:34:02,212 --> 00:34:04,318
- Well I think you're
pretty terrific, Mr. Hudson.

625
00:34:04,352 --> 00:34:06,423
A film like Giant doesn't
come along every day.

626
00:34:06,458 --> 00:34:08,322
- Well neither does a face
and figure like yours.

627
00:34:08,356 --> 00:34:12,015
You're so beautiful Liz,
a man has to squint.

628
00:34:12,050 --> 00:34:14,224
- That's the problem.

629
00:34:14,259 --> 00:34:18,228
Until you get rid of
that phony MGM veneer,

630
00:34:18,263 --> 00:34:20,748
you never will be an actress.

631
00:34:25,718 --> 00:34:27,789
- Excuse me, Mr. Stevens.

632
00:34:40,492 --> 00:34:43,219
[playful music]

633
00:34:47,740 --> 00:34:52,228
Is this what a real actress
is supposed to look like?

634
00:34:55,023 --> 00:34:59,407
Hey, I want it understood,
I'm more than a pretty face.

635
00:34:59,442 --> 00:35:00,305
Got that?

636
00:35:01,029 --> 00:35:03,411
[laughing]

637
00:35:11,039 --> 00:35:13,145
- God pity the guy that doesn't pay homage

638
00:35:13,180 --> 00:35:14,905
to that pretty face.

639
00:35:19,772 --> 00:35:23,155
[bright country music]

640
00:35:26,262 --> 00:35:27,504
- What you got there?

641
00:35:27,539 --> 00:35:30,473
- I got a little vodka,
mixed with a vermouthy.

642
00:35:30,507 --> 00:35:32,544
- I got no vermouthy, partner.

643
00:35:32,578 --> 00:35:36,237
- Well here partner, what are you having?

644
00:35:37,790 --> 00:35:39,171
- Kahlua.

645
00:35:39,206 --> 00:35:41,173
[laughing]

646
00:35:41,208 --> 00:35:42,864
- Hey, do you mind?

647
00:35:48,594 --> 00:35:52,909
You know what you get when
you mix vodka with Kahlua?

648
00:36:00,227 --> 00:36:01,780
Chocolate martini.

649
00:36:01,814 --> 00:36:04,196
[laughing]

650
00:36:08,338 --> 00:36:10,168
Chocolate martinis!

651
00:36:13,516 --> 00:36:15,725
[laughing]

652
00:36:19,694 --> 00:36:20,695
- City folk.

653
00:36:33,398 --> 00:36:34,537
- Good evening.

654
00:36:34,571 --> 00:36:36,332
Could you direct me to
Miss Taylor, please.

655
00:36:36,366 --> 00:36:37,333
- I'm sorry, sir.

656
00:36:37,367 --> 00:36:38,886
- I've just flown into this place

657
00:36:38,920 --> 00:36:40,819
from an air core base in El Paso.

658
00:36:40,853 --> 00:36:42,441
I'm tired, I'm hungry,

659
00:36:42,476 --> 00:36:44,995
and I'd like to see Miss Elizabeth Taylor.

660
00:36:45,030 --> 00:36:45,686
I'm the husband?

661
00:36:45,720 --> 00:36:46,756
- Oh yes sir.

662
00:36:46,790 --> 00:36:50,829
I believe she's having
dinner with Mr. Hudson.

663
00:36:55,868 --> 00:36:58,077
[laughing]

664
00:36:58,112 --> 00:37:00,977
[emotional music]

665
00:37:17,994 --> 00:37:18,857
- Hello.

666
00:37:22,032 --> 00:37:23,241
I always seem to

667
00:37:23,275 --> 00:37:26,830
fall a little in love with my leading man.

668
00:37:30,282 --> 00:37:32,008
Guess I always will.

669
00:37:33,803 --> 00:37:34,873
It's nothing.

670
00:37:52,546 --> 00:37:56,860
- Well I guess everything
ain't perfect in paradise.

671
00:38:02,003 --> 00:38:04,592
- Come on, little one, let's go.

672
00:38:04,627 --> 00:38:08,941
It's nap time, we can get
up and play later, okay?

673
00:38:11,427 --> 00:38:12,255
- Thank you.

674
00:38:12,290 --> 00:38:13,532
My God am I having fun.

675
00:38:13,567 --> 00:38:15,741
- You will try to be pleasant, won't you?

676
00:38:15,776 --> 00:38:18,330
There's some people here
that could help you.

677
00:38:18,365 --> 00:38:20,090
- You know I haven't got
your talent, Elizabeth.

678
00:38:20,125 --> 00:38:21,126
I can't just snap my fingers

679
00:38:21,160 --> 00:38:22,886
and have any man do what I want.

680
00:38:22,921 --> 00:38:25,303
- Am I really so bad?

681
00:38:25,337 --> 00:38:26,304
- Bad, no.

682
00:38:26,338 --> 00:38:27,719
Spoiled, maybe.

683
00:38:30,515 --> 00:38:34,484
- I didn't mean for it
to turn out like this.

684
00:38:35,416 --> 00:38:37,073
I do love you.

685
00:38:37,107 --> 00:38:38,626
- When business permits.

686
00:38:38,661 --> 00:38:40,973
But why should I complain?

687
00:38:50,155 --> 00:38:52,295
- Come on, Bessie, have some bubbles.

688
00:38:52,330 --> 00:38:54,608
- [laughing] Rock.

689
00:38:54,642 --> 00:38:56,541
- What's the skinny on Rain Tree?

690
00:38:56,575 --> 00:38:57,990
- Strictly hush hush.

691
00:38:58,025 --> 00:39:00,027
The South loses, you know.

692
00:39:00,061 --> 00:39:01,131
- Good script?

693
00:39:01,166 --> 00:39:04,411
- I suppose it's sort of
a Scarlet O'Hara gone mad.

694
00:39:04,445 --> 00:39:06,205
But I don't get to kiss Clark Gable.

695
00:39:06,240 --> 00:39:08,035
I get that sweet pea.

696
00:39:12,660 --> 00:39:15,456
- I thought you were too tired to come.

697
00:39:15,491 --> 00:39:17,424
- Too tired to come, Michael.

698
00:39:17,458 --> 00:39:20,047
But Bessie Mae called and called.

699
00:39:20,081 --> 00:39:20,910
- And what?

700
00:39:20,944 --> 00:39:21,773
- She always wins.

701
00:39:21,807 --> 00:39:23,222
- Oh, yes.

702
00:39:23,257 --> 00:39:26,191
- I guess you wanna talk about, um.

703
00:39:26,225 --> 00:39:27,882
Well, you know.

704
00:39:27,917 --> 00:39:30,126
She has marital problems.

705
00:39:30,160 --> 00:39:31,748
- She does indeed.

706
00:39:34,130 --> 00:39:37,133
You know, I think Elizabeth's
biggest problem is,

707
00:39:37,167 --> 00:39:39,515
she can have any man she wants.

708
00:39:40,585 --> 00:39:42,621
- And that compelled you
to cavort in the pool

709
00:39:42,656 --> 00:39:45,728
with a couple of, what were they, Michael?

710
00:39:45,762 --> 00:39:46,763
Strippers?

711
00:39:46,798 --> 00:39:49,007
Who told everything to
Confidential Magazine.

712
00:39:49,041 --> 00:39:50,077
- Utter nonsense.

713
00:39:50,111 --> 00:39:52,666
These girls dropped by,
nothing really happened.

714
00:39:52,700 --> 00:39:55,807
And how was I to know
they'd sell the story?

715
00:39:55,841 --> 00:39:56,670
- Michael.

716
00:39:56,704 --> 00:39:57,360
- Uh huh.

717
00:39:57,395 --> 00:39:58,396
- You live in Hollywood.

718
00:39:58,430 --> 00:40:01,813
And you're married to Elizabeth Taylor.

719
00:40:08,682 --> 00:40:10,891
- I heard she was in
Texas with whatshisname,

720
00:40:10,925 --> 00:40:12,306
doing God knows what.

721
00:40:12,340 --> 00:40:14,584
And what was I supposed to do here?

722
00:40:14,619 --> 00:40:16,552
Scoop up after the bloody dogs.

723
00:40:16,586 --> 00:40:19,727
You know, she sleeps every
night surrounded by her animals.

724
00:40:19,762 --> 00:40:22,074
I mean, where does that leave me?

725
00:40:22,109 --> 00:40:25,215
- Here's to the dogs of marriage.

726
00:40:25,250 --> 00:40:26,113
- Cheers.

727
00:40:27,114 --> 00:40:29,496
[laughing]

728
00:40:33,569 --> 00:40:35,571
- Why don't you just sleep here?

729
00:40:35,605 --> 00:40:37,331
- No no really, I'm fine.

730
00:40:37,365 --> 00:40:38,332
- You know, it's okay.

731
00:40:38,366 --> 00:40:39,644
I'll get in front of him.

732
00:40:39,678 --> 00:40:41,128
- What good will that do?

733
00:40:41,162 --> 00:40:45,132
- It'll keep him slow,
guide the way for him.

734
00:40:46,202 --> 00:40:47,065
- So long.

735
00:40:48,894 --> 00:40:49,550
- Be careful.

736
00:40:49,585 --> 00:40:51,828
- I'll call you tomorrow.

737
00:40:58,904 --> 00:41:01,493
[tense music]

738
00:41:31,696 --> 00:41:34,802
[tires screeching]

739
00:41:41,360 --> 00:41:43,742
[crashing]

740
00:42:20,158 --> 00:42:21,055
Okay.

741
00:42:22,332 --> 00:42:24,783
What? You can't breathe.

742
00:42:27,372 --> 00:42:28,615
It's a tooth.

743
00:42:28,649 --> 00:42:30,755
Mama's got it, it's okay.

744
00:42:35,587 --> 00:42:38,038
[indistinct chatter]

745
00:42:50,291 --> 00:42:51,396
- It's Monty Clift.

746
00:42:51,430 --> 00:42:54,606
- Stop it, get the hell out of here!

747
00:42:55,538 --> 00:42:57,851
Vultures, get out of here!

748
00:42:59,231 --> 00:43:00,094
Get away!

749
00:43:18,596 --> 00:43:21,391
[sirens blaring]

750
00:43:26,431 --> 00:43:27,294
Yoo hoo!

751
00:43:28,226 --> 00:43:28,709
Monty!

752
00:43:28,744 --> 00:43:30,124
Here he is, Monty.

753
00:43:30,159 --> 00:43:34,542
Your replacement if you're
not back on the set in a week.

754
00:43:34,577 --> 00:43:35,889
Now, he's good, baby.

755
00:43:35,923 --> 00:43:38,236
Trained in the method, you know.

756
00:43:38,270 --> 00:43:39,099
- Oh no.

757
00:43:39,133 --> 00:43:39,996
- Yes.

758
00:43:40,928 --> 00:43:43,655
I've missed you, you sweet old disaster.

759
00:43:43,690 --> 00:43:45,139
But you look great.

760
00:43:45,174 --> 00:43:46,175
- So they tell me.

761
00:43:46,209 --> 00:43:47,245
- Well they're right.

762
00:43:47,279 --> 00:43:51,007
- Why are you so excited
about, what's going on?

763
00:43:51,042 --> 00:43:53,596
- I ran into Mike Todd again last night.

764
00:43:53,631 --> 00:43:54,459
- Oh.

765
00:43:54,493 --> 00:43:55,840
- He's really great fun.

766
00:43:55,874 --> 00:43:59,671
[sighs] And so different from Michael.

767
00:43:59,706 --> 00:44:01,777
- What about Michael?

768
00:44:01,811 --> 00:44:03,779
- What about Michael?

769
00:44:07,127 --> 00:44:09,405
[phone ringing]

770
00:44:09,439 --> 00:44:10,924
- Michael Wilding.

771
00:44:10,958 --> 00:44:12,650
- Michael, it's Elizabeth.

772
00:44:12,684 --> 00:44:14,134
- Elizabeth, so nice to hear you.

773
00:44:14,168 --> 00:44:16,723
Tell me, how's Monty getting along?

774
00:44:16,757 --> 00:44:18,069
- Oh he's fine, fine.

775
00:44:18,103 --> 00:44:19,104
Um, Michael.

776
00:44:20,381 --> 00:44:22,729
I need you to know that I love you

777
00:44:22,763 --> 00:44:24,316
and I will always love you.

778
00:44:24,351 --> 00:44:25,559
- That's very comforting.

779
00:44:25,593 --> 00:44:27,388
- What I'm trying to say,

780
00:44:27,423 --> 00:44:28,942
and I want you to hear it from me

781
00:44:28,976 --> 00:44:31,945
before it appears in the papers,

782
00:44:31,979 --> 00:44:35,293
darling, I filed for legal separation.

783
00:44:39,504 --> 00:44:40,505
- Well thanks, but I'd rather

784
00:44:40,539 --> 00:44:42,024
have read it in the newspapers.

785
00:44:42,058 --> 00:44:43,335
- Yes?

786
00:44:43,370 --> 00:44:47,857
- I could have pretended it had
to do with two other people.

787
00:45:05,150 --> 00:45:08,395
- You tell me if I'm
interrupting, I'll get lost.

788
00:45:08,429 --> 00:45:10,708
- Not at all Mike, we
were waiting for you.

789
00:45:10,742 --> 00:45:13,572
- Yes we were, though I'm not sure why.

790
00:45:13,607 --> 00:45:14,470
- Are you leaving?

791
00:45:14,504 --> 00:45:15,574
- Me? No, why?

792
00:45:15,609 --> 00:45:16,437
This is my office.

793
00:45:16,472 --> 00:45:17,300
It says so on the door.

794
00:45:17,335 --> 00:45:18,129
Benny Thau.

795
00:45:18,163 --> 00:45:19,993
- I thought you was going some place.

796
00:45:20,027 --> 00:45:23,272
- Benny, I think he's being subtle.

797
00:45:23,306 --> 00:45:26,171
- Oh. [chuckling]

798
00:45:29,830 --> 00:45:31,729
Hey, excuse me.

799
00:45:31,763 --> 00:45:34,559
- Well don't run off, Benny.

800
00:45:34,593 --> 00:45:36,009
Please, don't run off.

801
00:45:36,043 --> 00:45:38,114
- Please, play nice Mike.

802
00:45:39,391 --> 00:45:42,705
- Well I'm not used to being
summoned this way, Mr. Todd.

803
00:45:42,740 --> 00:45:44,569
