- You don't have to.

2108
01:49:16,446 --> 01:49:17,896
You want to?

2109
01:49:17,930 --> 01:49:19,587
- She's my wife, I have to.

2110
01:49:19,622 --> 01:49:21,796
[sighs]

2111
01:49:22,659 --> 01:49:23,626
What do you wanna do?

2112
01:49:23,660 --> 01:49:25,869
- I want to love you.

2113
01:49:25,904 --> 01:49:27,491
You said you wanted to
get more out of life,

2114
01:49:27,526 --> 01:49:29,183
and that's what we've got.

2115
01:49:29,217 --> 01:49:30,287
We are more!

2116
01:49:30,322 --> 01:49:31,565
- What we get in life, Elizabeth,

2117
01:49:31,599 --> 01:49:33,014
is that we get to love a little,

2118
01:49:33,049 --> 01:49:35,430
just a little, and then
we get to die, a lot.

2119
01:49:35,465 --> 01:49:36,570
- I don't want to die!

2120
01:49:36,604 --> 01:49:37,812
- [laughs]

2121
01:49:37,847 --> 01:49:41,091
I'll tell them when I get there, hmm?

2122
01:49:42,299 --> 01:49:43,162
- Richard.

2123
01:49:43,197 --> 01:49:46,234
- Oh, I thought I could get away with it.

2124
01:49:46,269 --> 01:49:47,615
- With what?

2125
01:49:47,650 --> 01:49:48,754
- With you.

2126
01:49:50,273 --> 01:49:51,999
I'm drowning in you.

2127
01:49:54,242 --> 01:49:55,658
You're an ocean.

2128
01:49:55,692 --> 01:49:58,730
[emotional music]

2129
01:50:03,079 --> 01:50:06,634
- You're not actually leaving, are you?

2130
01:50:07,566 --> 01:50:08,671
- Yes I am.

2131
01:50:08,705 --> 01:50:09,844
- Damn you, Richard.

2132
01:50:09,879 --> 01:50:11,363
How dare you run away from me,

2133
01:50:11,397 --> 01:50:13,158
I've given up everything for you!

2134
01:50:13,192 --> 01:50:15,643
I've made a spectacle
out of myself for you!

2135
01:50:15,678 --> 01:50:16,402
- For me?

2136
01:50:16,437 --> 01:50:17,334
- Yes!

2137
01:50:17,369 --> 01:50:18,819
- Love, you have thrived for years

2138
01:50:18,853 --> 01:50:20,855
on the Elizabeth Taylor merry-go-round,

2139
01:50:20,890 --> 01:50:23,996
and I expect that you always shall.

2140
01:50:24,963 --> 01:50:26,965
[slaps]

2141
01:50:28,829 --> 01:50:31,348
At least until your looks go.

2142
01:50:35,076 --> 01:50:35,939
- Richard!

2143
01:50:37,561 --> 01:50:39,184
[door slams]

2144
01:50:39,218 --> 01:50:41,220
[cries]

2145
01:50:50,057 --> 01:50:51,472
[car turns]

2146
01:50:51,506 --> 01:50:54,199
[cries]

2147
01:50:54,233 --> 01:50:57,029
[tires screech]

2148
01:50:57,064 --> 01:50:59,066
[cries]

2149
01:51:09,663 --> 01:51:13,667
[music gets more suspenseful]

2150
01:51:14,598 --> 01:51:17,187
[phone rings]

2151
01:51:23,746 --> 01:51:26,369
- Am I glad to see those eyes open?

2152
01:51:26,403 --> 01:51:27,542
- Oh, Mick.

2153
01:51:27,577 --> 01:51:31,719
- Our underwriters are so
thrilled, I should mention.

2154
01:51:31,754 --> 01:51:34,066
- It's not what you think.

2155
01:51:37,345 --> 01:51:39,175
Where's Eddie?

2156
01:51:39,209 --> 01:51:41,108
- Eddie's gone, dear.

2157
01:51:41,142 --> 01:51:42,488
Some time now.

2158
01:51:42,523 --> 01:51:43,627
- Ah yes.

2159
01:51:43,662 --> 01:51:45,491
I'd forgotten.

2160
01:51:45,526 --> 01:51:48,460
I'd forget my head if it wasn't ...

2161
01:51:49,357 --> 01:51:51,774
I've been a bad girl, Mike.

2162
01:51:51,808 --> 01:51:53,465
Did you see this?

2163
01:51:53,499 --> 01:51:55,087
It's from the Vatican newspaper.

2164
01:51:55,122 --> 01:51:59,367
I didn't even know the
Pope had a newspaper.

2165
01:51:59,402 --> 01:52:02,405
No-one's gonna tell me
who I can and cannot love.

2166
01:52:02,439 --> 01:52:03,475
- Ah.

2167
01:52:03,509 --> 01:52:04,545
Ignore it.

2168
01:52:04,579 --> 01:52:05,546
- And they say I'm some sort of

2169
01:52:05,580 --> 01:52:07,065
erotic vagrant.

2170
01:52:07,099 --> 01:52:08,791
Whatever the hell that is.

2171
01:52:08,825 --> 01:52:09,861
- It ain't flattering.

2172
01:52:09,895 --> 01:52:12,035
- It's a lie is what it is.

2173
01:52:12,070 --> 01:52:13,692
I mean, I love my children!

2174
01:52:13,727 --> 01:52:15,625
I'm a wonderful mother.

2175
01:52:15,659 --> 01:52:17,903
I am, you can ask anyone.

2176
01:52:18,973 --> 01:52:20,319
God, Mike, what if they try to take

2177
01:52:20,354 --> 01:52:21,907
little Marie away from me?

2178
01:52:21,942 --> 01:52:24,945
I've gotta wire my lawyers,
I can't let that happen.

2179
01:52:24,979 --> 01:52:27,533
- Nobody's gonna take your kid.

2180
01:52:27,568 --> 01:52:30,605
You just concentrate on giving
your feet back under you.

2181
01:52:30,640 --> 01:52:31,606
- Can you sue the Pope?

2182
01:52:31,641 --> 01:52:34,023
- [laughs]

2183
01:52:36,439 --> 01:52:37,820
Get yourself up.

2184
01:52:37,854 --> 01:52:38,993
We'll get on down to his kid,

2185
01:52:39,028 --> 01:52:41,202
put you on a barge and
finish this picture.

2186
01:52:41,237 --> 01:52:43,204
- Well I don't know when
I'm going to be able to.

2187
01:52:43,239 --> 01:52:44,447
- I do.

2188
01:52:44,481 --> 01:52:45,897
Real soon.

2189
01:52:45,931 --> 01:52:48,347
[phone rings]

2190
01:52:48,382 --> 01:52:50,142
- Where's the old Welshman?

2191
01:52:50,177 --> 01:52:51,557
- Putting his wife on a plane.

2192
01:52:51,592 --> 01:52:52,869
- Oh?

2193
01:52:52,904 --> 01:52:56,010
- Yep, Sybil decided to take
the kids back to London.

2194
01:52:56,045 --> 01:52:58,875
Can't say I blame her, can you?

2195
01:53:00,290 --> 01:53:01,602
- Hmm.

2196
01:53:01,636 --> 01:53:03,017
- Hey, hey, no.

2197
01:53:04,432 --> 01:53:05,882
What are you doing?

2198
01:53:05,917 --> 01:53:08,540
- Escaia, what is that,
that's an island, isn't it?

2199
01:53:08,574 --> 01:53:11,405
What a break that would
be, the sea, the salt air.

2200
01:53:11,439 --> 01:53:12,475
- And the moonlight.

2201
01:53:12,509 --> 01:53:13,959
- [laughs]

2202
01:53:13,994 --> 01:53:16,444
Does Escaia have a great moon?

2203
01:53:16,479 --> 01:53:17,929
- I'm afraid so.

2204
01:53:18,792 --> 01:53:20,310
[laughs]

2205
01:53:20,345 --> 01:53:22,416
[kisses]

2206
01:53:25,074 --> 01:53:28,387
[light happy music]

2207
01:53:28,422 --> 01:53:31,874
[speaks in foreign language]

2208
01:53:31,908 --> 01:53:34,635
- God, will these hyenas go away?

2209
01:53:34,669 --> 01:53:36,430
- But love, how else am I to become

2210
01:53:36,464 --> 01:53:38,190
a Hollywood star?

2211
01:53:38,225 --> 01:53:40,675
Patience, patience, you vultures!

2212
01:53:40,710 --> 01:53:43,161
Take one last tear at our tender flesh,

2213
01:53:43,195 --> 01:53:47,441
because soon we will end
this endless venture.

2214
01:53:47,475 --> 01:53:49,098
- Excuse me, can I come through?

2215
01:53:49,132 --> 01:53:50,685
- Wait, I can't hear.

2216
01:53:50,720 --> 01:53:52,756
- Is that some new jewel?

2217
01:53:52,791 --> 01:53:54,793
- Oh yes, this is a little emerald broach

2218
01:53:54,828 --> 01:53:56,450
Richard bought me at Bulgarry.

2219
01:53:56,484 --> 01:53:57,900
- Yes, I introduced her to beer,

2220
01:53:57,934 --> 01:53:59,625
she introduced me to Bulgarry.

2221
01:53:59,660 --> 01:54:00,903
- Are you two going to marry?

2222
01:54:00,937 --> 01:54:02,076
- Marry a girl?

2223
01:54:02,111 --> 01:54:03,491
Never.

2224
01:54:03,526 --> 01:54:05,735
- Then what's the deal?

2225
01:54:05,769 --> 01:54:07,219
- Well,

2226
01:54:07,254 --> 01:54:08,738
not sure I should share this with you,

2227
01:54:08,772 --> 01:54:10,015
it's such a private thought,

2228
01:54:10,050 --> 01:54:13,156
but sometimes the heart
speaks and you have to.

2229
01:54:13,191 --> 01:54:14,778
I always believed that I
was a child of destiny.

2230
01:54:14,813 --> 01:54:16,056
If that's true,

2231
01:54:16,919 --> 01:54:20,094
then Richard Burton's surely my fate.

2232
01:54:20,129 --> 01:54:22,269
- That's sweet, love.

2233
01:54:22,303 --> 01:54:24,340
[press shout]

2234
01:54:24,374 --> 01:54:26,307
[cameras click]

2235
01:54:26,342 --> 01:54:28,931
[phone rings]

2236
01:54:30,484 --> 01:54:32,382
[church bell rings]

2237
01:54:32,417 --> 01:54:33,763
- Darling, what is it?

2238
01:54:33,797 --> 01:54:35,523
- That's enough destiny for one day.

2239
01:54:35,558 --> 01:54:38,457
- Ooh, are you in one of
your black Welsh moods?

2240
01:54:38,492 --> 01:54:39,734
- I received this.

2241
01:54:39,769 --> 01:54:40,874
- Hmm, from who?

2242
01:54:40,908 --> 01:54:42,323
- Whom.

2243
01:54:42,358 --> 01:54:43,221
- Whoooom.

2244
01:54:44,429 --> 01:54:46,155
- Sir Lawrence Olivier.

2245
01:54:46,189 --> 01:54:47,639
So Larry asks me a question,

2246
01:54:47,673 --> 01:54:48,951
do I want to be a household name

2247
01:54:48,985 --> 01:54:52,092
or do I want to be a great actor?

2248
01:54:52,126 --> 01:54:53,817
- Well, what do you want?

2249
01:54:53,852 --> 01:54:54,957
- Both.

2250
01:54:54,991 --> 01:54:56,751
[birds tweet]

2251
01:54:56,786 --> 01:54:59,237
[big dramatic music]

2252
01:54:59,271 --> 01:55:01,549
[men shout]

2253
01:55:09,903 --> 01:55:12,146
They've all folded their tents.

2254
01:55:12,181 --> 01:55:14,148
Romans and Egyptians,

2255
01:55:14,942 --> 01:55:17,255
and they've all gone home!

2256
01:55:18,739 --> 01:55:19,982
Battle's over.

2257
01:55:20,775 --> 01:55:22,881
- Battle, is that what it's been?

2258
01:55:22,916 --> 01:55:24,641
- From day one, yes.

2259
01:55:31,131 --> 01:55:33,443
- So where do we go now?

2260
01:55:33,478 --> 01:55:36,964
- Some place terrifying, like reality.

2261
01:55:37,827 --> 01:55:39,967
- Oh, do we have to?

2262
01:55:40,002 --> 01:55:41,969
- No, we could always

2263
01:55:42,797 --> 01:55:45,731
stay intoxicated for lovely always.

2264
01:55:49,252 --> 01:55:51,841
- I've always hated the end of filming.

2265
01:55:51,875 --> 01:55:54,395
[water runs]

2266
01:55:55,603 --> 01:55:57,674
People rush together and make

2267
01:55:57,709 --> 01:56:00,022
some intense crazy family,

2268
01:56:00,056 --> 01:56:03,128
and then everybody goes their own way

2269
01:56:03,991 --> 01:56:07,305
and, it's like 20 forms of abandonment

2270
01:56:08,789 --> 01:56:09,755
all at once.

2271
01:56:11,688 --> 01:56:14,208
- Everything ends, Elizabeth.

2272
01:56:15,969 --> 01:56:18,523
[emotional music]

2273
01:56:18,557 --> 01:56:19,627
- Everything?

2274
01:56:21,043 --> 01:56:22,423
- The truth is,

2275
01:56:23,873 --> 01:56:27,325
you always knew I could never leave her.

2276
01:56:28,395 --> 01:56:29,603
- I understand.

2277
01:56:30,949 --> 01:56:32,364
She's a good woman.

2278
01:56:33,296 --> 01:56:37,059
That's what everyone tells me, constantly.

2279
01:56:38,129 --> 01:56:39,647
She stood by you all these years,

2280
01:56:39,682 --> 01:56:42,823
through all your bad behavior.

2281
01:56:42,857 --> 01:56:45,032
- Yes, I know the story.

2282
01:56:49,174 --> 01:56:51,349
- So should we go home?

2283
01:56:51,383 --> 01:56:52,246
- Yes.

2284
01:56:55,560 --> 01:56:57,355
- Our separate homes?

2285
01:56:59,391 --> 01:57:00,254
- Yes.

2286
01:57:01,669 --> 01:57:03,982
- I could make you stay.

2287
01:57:04,017 --> 01:57:05,052
- Yes.

2288
01:57:08,780 --> 01:57:10,161
- Then I won't.

2289
01:57:23,312 --> 01:57:24,830
- Please, Mr Burton.

2290
01:57:24,865 --> 01:57:27,557
Please, would you hold that please?

2291
01:57:27,592 --> 01:57:29,076
Right there.

2292
01:57:29,111 --> 01:57:30,215
- Thank you, sir.

2293
01:57:30,250 --> 01:57:31,561
- Could I just get one more?

2294
01:57:31,596 --> 01:57:32,562
- What's that for?

2295
01:57:32,597 --> 01:57:33,253
- Oh, it's for Mrs Taylor

2296
01:57:33,287 --> 01:57:34,840
in case that she needs.

2297
01:57:34,875 --> 01:57:36,118
- Take it away, Miss Taylor will be fine.

2298
01:57:36,152 --> 01:57:37,740
- This way please.

2299
01:57:39,811 --> 01:57:40,777
- Thank you.

2300
01:57:40,812 --> 01:57:41,882
- Just turn around slowly, Mr Burton.

2301
01:57:41,916 --> 01:57:43,090
Right there.

2302
01:57:43,125 --> 01:57:44,885
There, thank you.

2303
01:57:44,919 --> 01:57:47,060
- Could you just give me one more?

2304
01:57:47,094 --> 01:57:48,578
[emotional music]

2305
01:57:48,613 --> 01:57:50,787
Would you mind looking this way, sir?

2306
01:57:50,822 --> 01:57:51,685
Please?

2307
01:57:53,238 --> 01:57:55,413
Excuse me, Mr Burton?

2308
01:57:55,447 --> 01:57:56,793
- Go ahead.

2309
01:57:56,828 --> 01:57:59,348
[car drives]

2310
01:58:01,591 --> 01:58:04,180
[birds tweet]

2311
01:58:10,842 --> 01:58:11,843
- You?

2312
01:58:11,877 --> 01:58:13,362
[children laugh]

2313
01:58:13,396 --> 01:58:14,397
Lovely!

2314
01:58:14,432 --> 01:58:16,089
- Come on Grandma, let's go play!

2315
01:58:16,123 --> 01:58:17,469
- Oh wait, let us be alone for a bit,

2316
01:58:17,504 --> 01:58:19,126
and then we'll come see you, okay?

2317
01:58:19,161 --> 01:58:21,232
- Run along, I'll be up later, all right?

2318
01:58:21,266 --> 01:58:22,957
[children giggle]

2319
01:58:22,992 --> 01:58:24,821
Oh, Elizabeth!

2320
01:58:24,856 --> 01:58:26,306
This is a dream.

2321
01:58:27,134 --> 01:58:29,343
An absolute dream.

2322
01:58:29,378 --> 01:58:31,690
It's perfect for the children,

2323
01:58:31,725 --> 01:58:36,039
you have everything you
could possibly need here.

2324
01:58:36,074 --> 01:58:37,869
- Well, except a man.

2325
01:58:39,664 --> 01:58:40,768
Oh Mummy, have you heard,

2326
01:58:40,803 --> 01:58:45,290
since we stopped shooting,
Fox has fired everyone?

2327
01:58:45,325 --> 01:58:48,431
And Walter Wanger, and
poor Joe Mankiewicz,

2328
01:58:48,466 --> 01:58:50,053
now he should have gotten a medal

2329
01:58:50,088 --> 01:58:52,021
for having to deal with me.

2330
01:58:52,055 --> 01:58:53,402
- Elizabeth.

2331
01:58:53,436 --> 01:58:56,853
You must really try and
put Richard behind you.

2332
01:58:56,888 --> 01:58:58,338
- Well I've put the
English channel between us,

2333
01:58:58,372 --> 01:59:00,616
that's a start, isn't it?

2334
01:59:02,963 --> 01:59:05,414
- It's so strange, you know.

2335
01:59:06,208 --> 01:59:08,002
You and Eddie bought this house

2336
01:59:08,037 --> 01:59:10,591
and then the scandal.

2337
01:59:10,626 --> 01:59:11,696
Liz Scandale.

2338
01:59:13,180 --> 01:59:15,044
Oh, honestly, you'd think the press

2339
01:59:15,078 --> 01:59:17,564
would have more to write about.

2340
01:59:17,598 --> 01:59:20,256
[laughs]

2341
01:59:20,291 --> 01:59:23,984
So, you really haven't seen him, since?

2342
01:59:24,018 --> 01:59:25,606
- The parting was amicable.

2343
01:59:25,641 --> 01:59:26,573
And mutual.

2344
01:59:27,815 --> 01:59:29,886
[laughs]

2345
01:59:29,921 --> 01:59:30,956
[phone rings]

2346
01:59:30,991 --> 01:59:31,854
Oh.

2347
01:59:36,238 --> 01:59:40,207
[speaks in foreign language]

2348
01:59:41,070 --> 01:59:41,933
Oh.

2349
01:59:44,625 --> 01:59:45,626
Well, hello.

2350
01:59:49,941 --> 01:59:50,942
How are you?

2351
01:59:52,012 --> 01:59:54,670
[people laugh]

2352
01:59:57,190 --> 02:00:00,434
[car drives off]

2353
02:00:00,469 --> 02:00:01,332
Hello.

2354
02:00:02,747 --> 02:00:04,266
- Miss Taylor!

2355
02:00:04,300 --> 02:00:06,751
- Please, call me Elizabeth.

2356
02:00:07,717 --> 02:00:08,649
- This way.

2357
02:00:09,374 --> 02:00:10,686
May I take your coat?

2358
02:00:10,720 --> 02:00:12,722
- No, I'm fine.

2359
02:00:12,757 --> 02:00:15,484
[people murmur]

2360
02:00:25,701 --> 02:00:26,667
- You've been well?

2361
02:00:26,702 --> 02:00:28,013
- Mmm, very busy.

2362
02:00:28,048 --> 02:00:29,014
- Good.

2363
02:00:29,049 --> 02:00:29,877
- You?

2364
02:00:29,912 --> 02:00:31,500
- Oh, flat, stale.

2365
02:00:32,846 --> 02:00:34,572
Unprofitable.

2366
02:00:34,606 --> 02:00:35,469
- Mmm.

2367
02:00:36,712 --> 02:00:39,577
I keep busy working on the chalet, mostly.

2368
02:00:39,611 --> 02:00:42,096
It's so beautiful, the children love it.

2369
02:00:42,131 --> 02:00:43,270
- Work.

2370
02:00:43,305 --> 02:00:45,790
That's what you need, real work, not this

2371
02:00:45,824 --> 02:00:47,274
doily arranging.

2372
02:00:48,137 --> 02:00:50,312
Have you read the script?

2373
02:00:50,346 --> 02:00:52,210
- Is that why you wanted to see me?

2374
02:00:52,245 --> 02:00:53,867
Talk about the VIP's?

2375
02:00:53,901 --> 02:00:54,971
- I've always wanted to see you.

2376
02:00:55,006 --> 02:00:58,768
Life is worthless without you, but ...

2377
02:00:58,803 --> 02:01:00,149
You have seen the script,

2378
02:01:00,183 --> 02:01:03,394
I know it's lightweight, but the deal ...

2379
02:01:03,428 --> 02:01:05,188
- And you really think that's a good idea?

2380
02:01:05,223 --> 02:01:06,742
Us working together?

2381
02:01:06,776 --> 02:01:08,191
- Why not?

2382
02:01:08,226 --> 02:01:12,334
It's half me and each,
London, you like London.

2383
02:01:15,233 --> 02:01:17,408
- And where will you be?

2384
02:01:18,512 --> 02:01:20,825
- Well, London, of course.

2385
02:01:22,171 --> 02:01:24,242
- I mean, Sybil's in London.

2386
02:01:24,277 --> 02:01:25,450
Your family.

2387
02:01:26,831 --> 02:01:27,694
- Yes.

2388
02:01:30,213 --> 02:01:32,319
Ah, thank you for that.

2389
02:01:33,320 --> 02:01:35,322
- Oh, you're welcome.

2390
02:01:35,357 --> 02:01:37,531
[pours]

2391
02:01:39,740 --> 02:01:40,569
- Richard,

2392
02:01:40,603 --> 02:01:43,123
I don't ever want you to hate me.

2393
02:01:43,157 --> 02:01:44,642
- Oh, I couldn't possibly--

2394
02:01:44,676 --> 02:01:46,437
- And lose for respect
for me, and think I'm--

2395
02:01:46,471 --> 02:01:48,956
- What's got into you, lovey?

2396
02:01:50,303 --> 02:01:52,201
- You used to call me Ocean.

2397
02:01:52,235 --> 02:01:53,892
- Well, I still do.

2398
02:01:55,273 --> 02:01:56,309
My ocean.

2399
02:01:57,896 --> 02:01:59,898
To me, you're boundless.

2400
02:02:02,280 --> 02:02:05,318
[concerned music]

2401
02:02:06,664 --> 02:02:10,253
- I've had a great deal time to think.

2402
02:02:10,288 --> 02:02:11,462
And Richard,

2403
02:02:12,911 --> 02:02:13,843
I need you.

2404
02:02:15,017 --> 02:02:16,881
All the time, I need you.

2405
02:02:16,915 --> 02:02:19,021
I know you don't want to marry
me or you can't marry me,

2406
02:02:19,055 --> 02:02:20,712
I've accepted that,

2407
