02:15:39,234 --> 02:15:41,305
- No so, like the sailor, I take comfort

2676
02:15:41,340 --> 02:15:45,654
there off into misty distant
hooting of your little horn.

2677
02:15:47,415 --> 02:15:49,486
[laughs]

2678
02:15:51,798 --> 02:15:53,524
- Bullseye!

2679
02:15:53,559 --> 02:15:55,354
[laughs]

2680
02:15:55,388 --> 02:15:57,218
- I am prepared to sacrifice many things

2681
02:15:57,252 --> 02:16:00,635
for our relationship, Elizabeth,

2682
02:16:00,669 --> 02:16:02,154
but to my dignity ...

2683
02:16:02,188 --> 02:16:03,672
- Oh, dignity?

2684
02:16:03,707 --> 02:16:04,501
- No.

2685
02:16:04,535 --> 02:16:05,674
- Dickie's little dignity.

2686
02:16:05,709 --> 02:16:06,744
- That's enough.

2687
02:16:06,779 --> 02:16:08,125
- Yes, you gave up dignity
you popped the cork

2688
02:16:08,160 --> 02:16:09,540
on that bottle!

2689
02:16:10,507 --> 02:16:11,370
Pop!

2690
02:16:11,404 --> 02:16:13,889
What a shot, a shot heard round the world!

2691
02:16:13,924 --> 02:16:16,029
Dickie's popped his little cork!

2692
02:16:16,064 --> 02:16:17,376
Pop, pop, pop!

2693
02:16:18,170 --> 02:16:19,205
Pop!

2694
02:16:20,206 --> 02:16:21,759
[laughs]

2695
02:16:21,794 --> 02:16:23,554
- Snap, snap, snap,

2696
02:16:23,589 --> 02:16:25,694
you little viper!

2697
02:16:25,729 --> 02:16:26,971
- Stop it!

2698
02:16:27,006 --> 02:16:27,869
- Oh!

2699
02:16:30,216 --> 02:16:31,286
You missed.

2700
02:16:31,321 --> 02:16:32,839
Come on, come on.

2701
02:16:32,874 --> 02:16:35,014
[smashes]

2702
02:16:35,048 --> 02:16:37,879
[concerned music]

2703
02:16:39,812 --> 02:16:41,814
[cries]

2704
02:16:44,126 --> 02:16:47,716
This is the hymn of chicken, hmm?

2705
02:16:47,751 --> 02:16:49,822
- I don't like our games.

2706
02:16:51,272 --> 02:16:53,239
I hate our games.

2707
02:16:53,274 --> 02:16:55,068
[cries]

2708
02:16:55,103 --> 02:16:56,829
- Don't be sad, hmm?

2709
02:16:59,935 --> 02:17:01,247
- I'm not sad.

2710
02:17:05,044 --> 02:17:06,218
I feel lost.

2711
02:17:19,334 --> 02:17:20,956
[door opens]

2712
02:17:20,991 --> 02:17:22,095
- What on Earth?

2713
02:17:22,130 --> 02:17:24,650
Will you stop that dawdling!?

2714
02:17:25,789 --> 02:17:26,928
Come on!

2715
02:17:26,962 --> 02:17:27,825
[laughs]

2716
02:17:27,860 --> 02:17:28,654
[makes chicken noise]

2717
02:17:28,688 --> 02:17:30,103
- It's all of these bloody petticoats,

2718
02:17:30,138 --> 02:17:32,727
takes me, it's like getting
dressed five times over again,

2719
02:17:32,761 --> 02:17:34,246
not like you.

2720
02:17:34,280 --> 02:17:36,006
These pantyhose.

2721
02:17:36,040 --> 02:17:38,353
- Madam, may I remind thee

2722
02:17:38,388 --> 02:17:41,080
that I am thy husband and thy Lord,

2723
02:17:41,114 --> 02:17:42,081
thy life?

2724
02:17:42,115 --> 02:17:43,151
[kisses]

2725
02:17:43,185 --> 02:17:46,085
And like frumpet, thy ...

2726
02:17:46,119 --> 02:17:47,259
- Thy pain in the ass.

2727
02:17:47,293 --> 02:17:48,950
- Oh, yes indeed.

2728
02:17:48,984 --> 02:17:49,847
Come!

2729
02:17:51,677 --> 02:17:52,540
Ah.

2730
02:17:55,543 --> 02:17:57,717
Elizabeth, it's for you.

2731
02:18:01,065 --> 02:18:03,516
I feel a cocktail coming on.

2732
02:18:10,696 --> 02:18:12,180
Elizabeth?

2733
02:18:12,214 --> 02:18:13,319
What is it?

2734
02:18:14,976 --> 02:18:16,011
- Monty!

2735
02:18:16,046 --> 02:18:17,012
[cries]

2736
02:18:17,047 --> 02:18:18,290
Monty's dead!

2737
02:18:26,470 --> 02:18:27,713
- Let him go.

2738
02:18:29,231 --> 02:18:31,095
He was a broken heart.

2739
02:18:32,062 --> 02:18:34,513
Nobody could have saved him.

2740
02:18:36,342 --> 02:18:38,482
[emotional music]

2741
02:18:38,517 --> 02:18:40,967
- We were too busy being us.

2742
02:18:45,040 --> 02:18:46,766
I'd forgotten Monty.

2743
02:18:48,837 --> 02:18:51,599
- He fell in love, you were married,

2744
02:18:51,633 --> 02:18:54,567
he never expected anything from you.

2745
02:18:54,602 --> 02:18:55,879
[cries]

2746
02:18:55,913 --> 02:18:56,845
Even a job.

2747
02:18:58,502 --> 02:19:00,953
Reflections in a golden eye.

2748
02:19:04,543 --> 02:19:09,306
- He was the only one I
could tell everything to.

2749
02:19:09,341 --> 02:19:12,896
Even things that were very private.

2750
02:19:12,930 --> 02:19:14,035
- He loved you.

2751
02:19:14,069 --> 02:19:16,037
[cries]

2752
02:19:19,868 --> 02:19:20,835
- Bessy May.

2753
02:19:20,869 --> 02:19:23,044
[laughs]

2754
02:19:23,078 --> 02:19:24,666
He left Bessy May.

2755
02:19:32,985 --> 02:19:34,262
God, I had many proposals,

2756
02:19:34,296 --> 02:19:38,749
but he was the only man I
should have asked to marry me.

2757
02:19:41,269 --> 02:19:42,788
- Is that a fact?

2758
02:19:45,618 --> 02:19:47,724
Was it a drug overdose?

2759
02:19:51,831 --> 02:19:52,970
- A life over.

2760
02:19:54,247 --> 02:19:56,353
[sweeping dramatic music]

2761
02:19:56,388 --> 02:19:57,458
[audience applause]

2762
02:19:57,492 --> 02:19:58,769
- Elizabeth Taylor is not here tonight,

2763
02:19:58,804 --> 02:20:00,461
she's in the south of France,

2764
02:20:00,495 --> 02:20:02,359
accepting her Oscar
will be her dear friend,

2765
02:20:02,394 --> 02:20:04,465
Miss Anne Baxter.

2766
02:20:04,499 --> 02:20:05,673
- They just gave you an Oscar,

2767
02:20:05,707 --> 02:20:08,123
and you're complaining.

2768
02:20:08,158 --> 02:20:09,504
- I'm not complaining for me,

2769
02:20:09,539 --> 02:20:11,057
I'm complaining for you.

2770
02:20:11,092 --> 02:20:12,300
- Oh, I'm a chronic complainer,

2771
02:20:12,334 --> 02:20:13,888
I don't need help.

2772
02:20:14,992 --> 02:20:16,753
- Damn, this is your
fifth nomination, Richard.

2773
02:20:16,787 --> 02:20:19,100
You deserve the Oscar, not me.

2774
02:20:19,134 --> 02:20:19,687
- Shh.

2775
02:20:20,757 --> 02:20:24,657
We've named the yacht
after our three girls,

2776
02:20:25,727 --> 02:20:27,695
Kate, Liza and Maria,

2777
02:20:28,937 --> 02:20:29,800
Kalizma!

2778
02:20:30,870 --> 02:20:32,941
[laughs]

2779
02:20:34,495 --> 02:20:36,289
- I'm so happy.

2780
02:20:36,324 --> 02:20:37,187
- Oh.

2781
02:20:39,845 --> 02:20:40,915
It's quaintly comforting that

2782
02:20:40,949 --> 02:20:44,643
a mere yacht can make you happy, my love.

2783
02:20:47,991 --> 02:20:48,992
[men shout]

2784
02:20:49,026 --> 02:20:51,719
[cameras click]

2785
02:20:55,412 --> 02:20:56,827
- Thank you.

2786
02:20:56,862 --> 02:20:59,520
[seagulls cry]

2787
02:21:00,244 --> 02:21:01,660
Where are you going?

2788
02:21:01,694 --> 02:21:04,041
People are coming, we're gonna celebrate.

2789
02:21:04,076 --> 02:21:05,077
- Yes, I hadn't forgotten,

2790
02:21:05,111 --> 02:21:08,839
I'm taking a launch to
pick some of my mates.

2791
02:21:08,874 --> 02:21:10,047
- You mean those other drunks?

2792
02:21:10,082 --> 02:21:11,186
- No.

2793
02:21:11,221 --> 02:21:14,155
I mean the other actors,
the thespians, Elizabeth,

2794
02:21:14,189 --> 02:21:16,468
who have come from afar to celebrate

2795
02:21:16,502 --> 02:21:18,780
your crowning achievement.

2796
02:21:18,815 --> 02:21:19,678
- Hmm.

2797
02:21:20,955 --> 02:21:21,852
I was just asking.

2798
02:21:21,887 --> 02:21:22,888
- No you weren't.

2799
02:21:22,922 --> 02:21:24,959
You were concerned about
whether I was going to

2800
02:21:24,993 --> 02:21:27,271
fall off the wagon that
I've been clinging to

2801
02:21:27,306 --> 02:21:29,722
so desperately for the last 13 days,

2802
02:21:29,757 --> 02:21:32,242
and well, don't worry love,

2803
02:21:32,276 --> 02:21:36,764
because you see, I'm one of
its last remaining passengers.

2804
02:21:40,837 --> 02:21:41,700
Toodleoo.

2805
02:21:42,494 --> 02:21:46,152
[ship horn blows]

2806
02:21:46,187 --> 02:21:47,119
- Toodleoo.

2807
02:21:49,501 --> 02:21:50,605
[French music]

2808
02:21:50,640 --> 02:21:51,744
I can't tell you all of the, whatevers,

2809
02:21:51,779 --> 02:21:54,264
specifications, Richard knows them.

2810
02:21:54,298 --> 02:21:55,541
Bonjour, Jean Paul.

2811
02:21:55,576 --> 02:21:57,370
- Bonjour, Elizabeth!

2812
02:21:57,405 --> 02:21:59,027
- All I know is,

2813
02:21:59,062 --> 02:22:00,442
it feels like home.

2814
02:22:00,477 --> 02:22:03,342
[men shout]

2815
02:22:03,376 --> 02:22:06,863
[crowd murmurs]

2816
02:22:06,897 --> 02:22:08,243
- We win!

2817
02:22:08,278 --> 02:22:11,039
[laughs]

2818
02:22:11,074 --> 02:22:12,040
- Thank you very much.

2819
02:22:12,075 --> 02:22:12,938
Jean Paul!

2820
02:22:14,456 --> 02:22:16,320
[speaks in foreign language]

2821
02:22:16,355 --> 02:22:18,599
[laughs]

2822
02:22:20,117 --> 02:22:22,568
[pops cork]

2823
02:22:24,328 --> 02:22:25,398
- You're late.

2824
02:22:25,433 --> 02:22:26,883
- Oh.

2825
02:22:26,917 --> 02:22:29,679
And you're a very pretty girl.

2826
02:22:30,783 --> 02:22:32,992
- Richard, you started drinking again?

2827
02:22:33,027 --> 02:22:33,993
[laughs]

2828
02:22:34,028 --> 02:22:34,856
- Have I?

2829
02:22:34,891 --> 02:22:35,719
Hmm.

2830
02:22:36,893 --> 02:22:38,964
[laughs]

2831
02:22:44,659 --> 02:22:49,008
[country music]

2832
02:22:56,153 --> 02:22:57,327
- Thank you.

2833
02:22:59,916 --> 02:23:02,125
- Elizabeth, oh my darling!

2834
02:23:02,159 --> 02:23:03,367
[kisses]

2835
02:23:03,402 --> 02:23:06,578
Mrs Taylor, happy birthday, my dear.

2836
02:23:07,268 --> 02:23:08,821
I have to tell you, 40?

2837
02:23:08,856 --> 02:23:10,098
You don't even look--

2838
02:23:10,133 --> 02:23:12,411
- Well, how about my being
a Grandmother last year?

2839
02:23:12,445 --> 02:23:13,446
Would you believe it?

2840
02:23:13,481 --> 02:23:14,551
- I refuse to believe it.

2841
02:23:14,586 --> 02:23:15,552
- Oh, well then don't,

2842
02:23:15,587 --> 02:23:16,588
I need all the help I can get.

2843
02:23:16,622 --> 02:23:17,865
[laughs]

2844
02:23:17,899 --> 02:23:19,107
- I can't believe it,

2845
02:23:19,142 --> 02:23:21,351
who would allow Richard
to put on this shindig

2846
02:23:21,385 --> 02:23:22,559
here in Budapest?

2847
02:23:22,594 --> 02:23:25,389
But to fly in all these guests?

2848
02:23:25,424 --> 02:23:26,736
- Well Mother, we have to,

2849
02:23:26,770 --> 02:23:28,530
because he's shooting Bluebeard here,

2850
02:23:28,565 --> 02:23:30,153
and with eight wives, I don't want him

2851
02:23:30,187 --> 02:23:32,086
hanging around all those Bluebeard broads

2852
02:23:32,120 --> 02:23:33,466
without me.

2853
02:23:33,501 --> 02:23:34,536
- Oh, seriously.

2854
02:23:34,571 --> 02:23:35,537
- I don't!

2855
02:23:35,572 --> 02:23:36,331
[laughs]

2856
02:23:36,366 --> 02:23:37,263
- Here you go, Mom.

2857
02:23:37,298 --> 02:23:39,196
- I was painless, shall we say,

2858
02:23:39,231 --> 02:23:40,888
legs tied together.

2859
02:23:42,648 --> 02:23:43,787
- Oh dear.

2860
02:23:43,822 --> 02:23:45,582
Who's Richard boring over there now?

2861
02:23:45,617 --> 02:23:47,964
- Ah, it's the Swiss
ambassador and his wife.

2862
02:23:47,998 --> 02:23:49,034
- Hmm.

2863
02:23:49,068 --> 02:23:50,104
I see.

2864
02:23:50,138 --> 02:23:53,555
- Noah's Ark gently
flowed down my left thigh.

2865
02:23:53,590 --> 02:23:54,798
- [clears throat] Oui.

2866
02:23:54,833 --> 02:23:56,558
- Darling, not one of
your old stage stories.

2867
02:23:56,593 --> 02:23:59,216
Hmm, give the old Vic a break, will you?

2868
02:23:59,251 --> 02:23:59,838
- Oh.

2869
02:23:59,872 --> 02:24:00,908
- Please excuse us.

2870
02:24:00,942 --> 02:24:02,012
- I'm terribly sorry, she's terribly rude.

2871
02:24:02,047 --> 02:24:03,151
- Mother.

2872
02:24:03,186 --> 02:24:06,707
- I'm sorry, Richard, I
have to see this up close.

2873
02:24:06,741 --> 02:24:09,192
- Oh, of course, your highness.

2874
02:24:09,226 --> 02:24:10,676
- The Krup, isn't it?

2875
02:24:10,711 --> 02:24:12,264
The Krup diamond.

2876
02:24:12,298 --> 02:24:13,748
- Yes.

2877
02:24:13,783 --> 02:24:14,956
Little present from Richard.

2878
02:24:14,991 --> 02:24:17,441
- I saw it in the paper, front page.

2879
02:24:17,476 --> 02:24:19,581
- Yes, that's the way we like it, love.

2880
02:24:19,616 --> 02:24:21,480
Diamonds on the front page,

2881
02:24:21,514 --> 02:24:23,240
and bad reviews on the back.

2882
02:24:23,275 --> 02:24:25,795
[laughs]

2883
02:24:25,829 --> 02:24:28,487
Oh, you look a little thirsty, love,

2884
02:24:28,521 --> 02:24:30,558
let me fill you up.

2885
02:24:30,592 --> 02:24:32,111
- Thank you.

2886
02:24:32,146 --> 02:24:34,148
- The most vulgar thing I've ever seen.

2887
02:24:34,182 --> 02:24:36,633
[laughs]

2888
02:24:36,668 --> 02:24:38,255
- Would you like to try it on?

2889
02:24:38,290 --> 02:24:39,153
- Oh ...

2890
02:24:43,882 --> 02:24:48,127
- Well, doesn't look
so vulgar now, does it?

2891
02:24:48,162 --> 02:24:50,233
[laughs]

2892
02:24:57,827 --> 02:25:00,795
[traffic passes]

2893
02:25:01,693 --> 02:25:03,453
[door buzzes]

2894
02:25:03,487 --> 02:25:04,972
- Darling?

2895
02:25:05,006 --> 02:25:08,113
The scribbler is here from the whatever,

2896
02:25:08,147 --> 02:25:12,186
that journal, the cinematic magazine.

2897
02:25:12,220 --> 02:25:13,428
I'll handle it!

2898
02:25:15,258 --> 02:25:16,224
Ah--

2899
02:25:16,259 --> 02:25:17,087
- Mr Burton!

2900
02:25:17,122 --> 02:25:18,019
- Yes, Mr Durham.

2901
02:25:18,054 --> 02:25:18,848
- Durlam.

2902
02:25:18,882 --> 02:25:20,539
- Oh, whatever, it's nice to meet you.

2903
02:25:20,573 --> 02:25:21,713
Sit down.

2904
02:25:21,747 --> 02:25:22,955
- I'm extremely grateful--

2905
02:25:22,990 --> 02:25:26,856
- Sad to see that my beloved is ill today.

2906
02:25:26,890 --> 02:25:28,340
- I'm sorry, maybe I should come back.

2907
02:25:28,374 --> 02:25:29,375
- Oh, nothing serious,

2908
02:25:29,410 --> 02:25:31,550
we just think it's German measles.

2909
02:25:31,584 --> 02:25:33,034
- You're joking.

2910
02:25:34,242 --> 02:25:36,072
- She'll be up in a day.

2911
02:25:36,106 --> 02:25:37,936
We've prescribed her Italian vodka.

2912
02:25:37,970 --> 02:25:41,249
Quite remarkable, tastes like a paragoric.

2913
02:25:41,284 --> 02:25:43,665
[thunder rolls]

2914
02:25:43,700 --> 02:25:44,736
Go ahead.

2915
02:25:45,633 --> 02:25:46,496
- Sir.

2916
02:25:47,393 --> 02:25:48,222
- Your interview.

2917
02:25:48,256 --> 02:25:49,119
- Oh, yes.

2918
02:25:50,672 --> 02:25:51,812
- I hope you haven't come prepared to ask

2919
02:25:51,846 --> 02:25:55,539
us about the recent
flops we've been having.

2920
02:25:56,713 --> 02:25:58,542
- Richard, I can hear you!

2921
02:25:58,577 --> 02:25:59,785
- Yes.

2922
02:25:59,820 --> 02:26:02,546
We've only had four
flops in a row, actually,

2923
02:26:02,581 --> 02:26:05,342
but some of them had merit, small merit.

2924
02:26:05,377 --> 02:26:07,586
- I'm sure this gentleman
would prefer to come back

2925
02:26:07,620 --> 02:26:08,690
when it isn't raining.

2926
02:26:08,725 --> 02:26:09,726
- Not so.

2927
02:26:09,761 --> 02:26:12,039
He's a veritable duck.

2928
02:26:12,073 --> 02:26:13,005
Hmm?

2929
02:26:13,040 --> 02:26:14,904
You don't mind the rain, do you?

2930
02:26:14,938 --> 02:26:16,043
- Not at all.

2931
02:26:16,077 --> 02:26:17,320
- When it isn't raining,

2932
02:26:17,354 --> 02:26:20,599
perhaps you'll have
sunnier things to say, hmm?

2933
02:26:20,633 --> 02:26:22,083
- Hmm, yes, yes.

2934
02:26:27,675 --> 02:26:30,851
[church bell rings]

2935
02:26:35,648 --> 02:26:37,167
You're racing.

2936
02:26:37,202 --> 02:26:38,617
- We're crawling.

2937
02:26:38,651 --> 02:26:39,791
- I've always been of the opinion

2938
02:26:39,825 --> 02:26:42,517
that mother nature, like
one's mother in law,

2939
02:26:42,552 --> 02:26:45,486
should be visited, but sparingly.

2940
02:26:45,520 --> 02:26:48,454
- It's the drink that wears you out.

2941
02:26:48,489 --> 02:26:50,146
And the cigarettes.

2942
02:26:51,699 --> 02:26:54,667
- It's arthritis actually.

2943
02:26:54,702 --> 02:26:57,360
It reminds me, medication time.

2944
02:26:58,499 --> 02:27:01,122
- Oh Richard, I worry about you.

2945
02:27:01,157 --> 02:27:03,366
- Me too, that's why I drink.

2946
02:27:03,400 --> 02:27:04,988
[wind howls]

2947
02:27:05,023 --> 02:27:06,990
- You really regret
taking a few days here?

2948
02:27:07,025 --> 02:27:11,063
I mean, look around, the
chalet, the mountains ...

2949
02:27:11,098 --> 02:27:12,996
Did you ever believe you'd
have a life like this?

2950
02:27:13,031 --> 02:27:14,756
- Oh yes, this is
precisely the kind of life

2951
02:27:14,791 --> 02:27:16,448
I thought we'd be having.

2952
02:27:16,482 --> 02:27:20,210
Apart from our occasional
trip to this snow palace,

2953
02:27:20,245 --> 02:27:24,870
we have a life of hotel
rooms and rented houses,

2954
02:27:24,905 --> 02:27:27,045
and, oh yes, that yacht,

2955
02:27:27,079 --> 02:27:29,841
that luxuriously
appointed floating prison.

2956
02:27:29,875 --> 02:27:31,981
- I don't like your tone, Richard.

2957
02:27:32,015 --> 02:27:33,051
- It's a life,

2958
02:27:33,085 --> 02:27:34,915
or a half life, actually.

2959
02:27:34,949 --> 02:27:36,709
And to make up for the missing half,

2960
02:27:36,744 --> 02:27:38,539
I drink twice as much.

2961
02:27:38,573 --> 02:27:40,644
- Oh stop it, Richard.

2962
02:27:40,679 --> 02:27:43,233
- Oh, I'll stop, I'll die of drink,

2963
02:27:44,372 --> 02:27:48,549
and you shall go on
blithely in your half world.

2964
02:27:49,343 --> 02:27:51,793
- Do you have to say these things?

2965
02:27:51,828 --> 02:27:53,623
I mean, I know you think them,

2966
02:27:53,657 --> 02:27:55,487
but must you say them?

2967
02:27:55,521 --> 02:27:56,453
Constantly?

2968
02:28:00,872 --> 02:28:03,460
[plane flies]

2969
02:28:06,981 --> 02:28:08,293
Are you going to hold up?

2970
02:28:08,327 --> 02:28:09,501
- I'll hold up.

2971
02:28:09,535 --> 02:28:11,503
Bloody Marys'll hold me up.

2972
02:28:11,537 --> 02:28:14,264
Bob, two large Bloody Mary's.

2973
02:28:14,299 --> 02:28:15,162
- Okay.

2974
02:28:15,196 --> 02:28:16,197
- I hate to leave you,

2975
02:28:16,232 --> 02:28:17,750
New York is dreadful this time of year.

2976
02:28:17,785 --> 02:28:18,855
- Oh.

2977
02:28:18,890 --> 02:28:22,169
You go off to the coast, I'll be fine.

2978
02:28:22,203 --> 02:28:25,966
It's always dreadful out there anyway.

2979
02:28:26,000 --> 02:28:29,970
Always open season if you like small game.

2980
02:28:30,004 --> 02:28:31,523
- We haven't gone off on our separate ways

2981
02:28:31,557 --> 02:28:32,938
in a long time.

2982
02:28:34,767 --> 02:28:35,596
We're doing the right thing?

2983
02:28:35,630 --> 02:28:36,838
- [laughs]

2984
02:28:36,873 --> 02:28:40,808
It's been a long time since
we've done the right thing.

2985
02:28:40,842 --> 02:28:42,154
- Richard!

2986
02:28:42,189 --> 02:28:42,844
[laughs]

2987
02:28:42,879 --> 02:28:45,640
- Doing the right thing.

2988
02:28:45,675 --> 02:28:46,538
Huh.

2989
02:28:48,264 --> 02:28:50,714
It's like seeming and being.

2990
02:28:52,130 --> 02:28:53,717
Being and seeming.

2991
02:28:54,787 --> 02:28:56,651
The Dick and Liz Show.

2992
02:28:58,136 --> 02:29:01,070
We're like Laurel and Hardy.

2993
02:29:01,104 --> 02:29:04,038
- I've always been fond
of Lauren and Hardy.

2994
02:29:04,073 --> 02:29:05,695
- Oh yes, well we're not as cute,

2995
02:29:05,729 --> 02:29:06,730
not anymore.

2996
02:29:09,112 --> 02:29:11,804
Everybody's sick to death
of us, especially me.

2997
02:29:11,839 --> 02:29:12,840
[phone rings]

2998
02:29:12,874 --> 02:29:14,773
Especially me.

2999
02:29:14,807 --> 02:29:15,670
I know.

3000
02:29:16,671 --> 02:29:18,466
We need, new writers.

3001
02:29:19,778 --> 02:29:21,021
- Premier airlines, flight two,

3002
02:29:21,055 --> 02:29:22,505
two lost--

3003
02:29:22,539 --> 02:29:24,921
- That's my last plane.

3004
02:29:24,956 --> 02:29:26,923
- Miss Taylor, we'll escort you.

3005
02:29:26,958 --> 02:29:28,166
- You've been waiting for an hour.

3006
02:29:28,200 --> 02:29:31,100
Just so they know that it's you.

3007
02:29:34,034 --> 02:29:35,483
- Goodbye Daffy.

3008
02:29:39,073 --> 02:29:40,109
- Bye bye.

3009
02:29:48,738 --> 02:29:50,602
- Would you give this to the press?

3010
02:29:50,636 --> 02:29:52,121
[phone rings]

3011
02:29:52,155 --> 02:29:55,124
[slow sad music]

3012
02:29:56,125 --> 02:29:57,816
- Like this?

3013
02:29:57,850 --> 02:29:59,093
To the press?

3014
02:30:00,163 --> 02:30:02,269
- I just can't face him.

3015
02:30:02,303 --> 02:30:03,477
[cries]

3016
02:30:03,511 --> 02:30:06,031
I am convinced it would be
a good and constructive idea

3017
02:30:06,066 --> 02:30:09,690
if Richard and I were
separated for a while.

3018
02:30:09,724 --> 02:30:12,279
Maybe we loved each other too much.

3019
02:30:12,313 --> 02:30:15,489
I never believed such
a thing was possible.

3020
02:30:15,523 --> 02:30:18,250
But we have been in each
other's pockets constantly,

3021
02:30:18,285 --> 02:30:21,943
never being apart but for
matters of life and death.

3022
02:30:21,978 --> 02:30:23,221
I believe with all my heart

3023
02:30:23,255 --> 02:30:24,774
that the separation will ultimately

3024
02:30:24,808 --> 02:30:29,606
bring us back to where we
should be, and that's together.

3025
02:30:29,641 --> 02:30:32,713
It's just while during
this difficult time.

3026
02:30:32,747 --> 02:30:33,748
Pray for us.

3027
02:30:44,138 --> 02:30:47,107
[car horn blows]

3028
02:30:49,523 --> 02:30:52,629
[door buzzes]

3029
02:30:52,664 --> 02:30:55,253
[clock ticks]

3030
02:31:04,055 --> 02:31:05,366
[door opens]

3031
02:31:05,401 --> 02:31:06,264
- Evening.

3032
02:31:07,610 --> 02:31:09,025
I'm your date tonight.

3033
02:31:09,060 --> 02:31:10,751
- Oh, then you must be John Warner.

3034
02:31:10,785 --> 02:31:13,305
- Yes ma'am, there's no
question who you are.

3035
02:31:13,340 --> 02:31:14,548
- Oh, call me Elizabeth.

3036
02:31:14,582 --> 02:31:17,689
Well, I can't even remember a time,

3037
02:31:17,723 --> 02:31:19,691
I must have been a teenager

3038
02:31:19,725 --> 02:31:21,658
when I had my last blind date.

3039
02:31:21,693 --> 02:31:22,521
[laughs]

3040
02:31:22,556 --> 02:31:23,902
- Well we're all awfully grateful over

3041
02:31:23,936 --> 02:31:25,110
at the bicentennial committee

3042
02:31:25,145 --> 02:31:26,491
that you agreed to attend
our little ball here

3043
02:31:26,525 --> 02:31:27,561
in Washington.

3044
02:31:27,595 --> 02:31:31,737
- Well, consider it my patriotic duty.

3045
02:31:31,772 --> 02:31:33,498
So tell me about yourself.

3046
02:31:33,532 --> 02:31:35,051
- Well there's not much to tell.

3047
02:31:35,086 --> 02:31:36,570
I'm a Virginian, I got a farm down there,

3048
02:31:36,604 --> 02:31:38,365
I work in the government, and one day

3049
02:31:38,399 --> 02:31:39,849
I plan to run for Senator.

3050
02:31:39,883 --> 02:31:40,884
- Oh.

3051
02:31:40,919 --> 02:31:41,920
You have a farm?

3052
02:31:41,954 --> 02:31:42,886
- Yes ma'am.

3053
02:31:42,921 --> 02:31:43,922
- And you have animals?

3054
02:31:43,956 --> 02:31:44,923
- You betcha.

3055
02:31:44,957 --> 02:31:46,683
- I love animals.

3056
02:31:46,718 --> 02:31:49,030
[happy magical music]

3057
02:31:49,065 --> 02:31:51,447
[cow moos]

3058
02:31:53,034 --> 02:31:55,485
[dog barks]

3059
02:31:56,590 --> 02:31:59,110
[car passes]

3060
02:32:13,193 --> 02:32:14,539
It's so beautiful.

3061
02:32:15,781 --> 02:32:20,407
- It's nice of you coming
all the way out here with me.

3062
02:32:20,441 --> 02:32:22,271
- This is my childhood.

3063
02:32:22,305 --> 02:32:26,516
Really, I feel like I'm back in England.

3064
02:32:26,551 --> 02:32:27,517
- You like it?

3065
02:32:27,552 --> 02:32:28,760
- Mhmm,

3066
02:32:28,794 --> 02:32:29,657
yes.

3067
02:32:31,694 --> 02:32:35,249
Have you ever instantly fallen in love?

3068
02:32:36,147 --> 02:32:37,389
With a place.

3069
02:32:39,357 --> 02:32:42,532
- Tell me about yourself, Elizabeth.

3070
02:32:43,913 --> 02:32:47,158
- I'm still reeling from my
second divorce from Richard.

3071
02:32:47,192 --> 02:32:48,159
Richard Burton.

3072
02:32:48,193 --> 02:32:49,919
- Yes, I know who he is.

3073
02:32:49,953 --> 02:32:51,058
- Oh, you've met him?

3074
02:32:51,092 --> 02:32:52,197
- No.

3075
02:32:52,232 --> 02:32:54,061
But I've read about him.

3076
02:32:54,095 --> 02:32:55,787
Like everyone else in America.

3077
02:32:55,821 --> 02:32:57,754
[laughs]

3078
02:32:58,376 --> 02:32:59,687
- Well, for a change,

3079
02:32:59,722 --> 02:33:02,000
what you've read in the
papers is pretty much true.

3080
02:33:02,034 --> 02:33:04,485
I've had five husbands and five divorces.

3081
02:33:04,520 --> 02:33:07,005
- Sounds a little discouraging.

3082
02:33:07,039 --> 02:33:08,109
- Hmm.

3083
02:33:08,144 --> 02:33:09,180
Well ...

3084
02:33:11,009 --> 02:33:13,425
Only if you believe in love.

3085
02:33:18,154 --> 02:33:21,019
[celebratory big band music]

3086
02:33:21,053 --> 02:33:23,711
[crowd cheers]

3087
02:33:30,131 --> 02:33:32,927
[brakes screech]

3088
02:33:36,862 --> 02:33:38,381
- Howdy folks!

3089
02:33:38,416 --> 02:33:41,557
I'm John Warner and I'm looking
to be your next senator!

3090
02:33:41,591 --> 02:33:44,042
And this here's my lovely wife Elizabeth!

3091
02:33:44,076 --> 02:33:46,424
[crowd cheers]

3092
02:33:46,458 --> 02:33:50,773
Now remember folks, a vote
for me is a vote for her too!

3093
02:33:55,191 --> 02:33:58,298
[jolly band music]

3094
02:34:08,446 --> 02:34:12,277
- Oh, thank you, [laughs].

3095
02:34:13,727 --> 02:34:16,316
[birds tweet]

3096
02:34:17,903 --> 02:34:20,147
Now what do you say to
Republican fat cats?

3097
02:34:20,181 --> 02:34:21,631
- I wish you wouldn't say that.

3098
02:34:21,666 --> 02:34:22,667
- Oh God, I haven't even met them,

3099
02:34:22,701 --> 02:34:24,220
I've already said something wrong?

3100
02:34:24,255 --> 02:34:26,187
- You sound like you're
in the enemy party.

3101
02:34:26,222 --> 02:34:28,120
- Well, I'm your wife, that's my party.

3102
02:34:28,155 --> 02:34:29,743
[crowd applaud]

3103
02:34:29,777 --> 02:34:30,985
- And it is a privilege to introduce

3104
02:34:31,020 --> 02:34:33,781
the next senator from
the Old Dominion state,

3105
02:34:33,816 --> 02:34:37,716
our new senator, John
Warner and Mrs Warner!

3106
02:34:43,964 --> 02:34:45,103
- Well thank you.

3107
02:34:45,137 --> 02:34:47,105
I would like to introduce the real power

3108
02:34:47,139 --> 02:34:49,280
behind my campaign:

3109
02:34:49,314 --> 02:34:52,248
my country wife, Elizabeth.

3110
02:34:52,283 --> 02:34:55,009
[crowd applaud]

3111
02:34:57,322 --> 02:34:58,910
- Now thank you all for your wonderful

3112
02:34:58,944 --> 02:35:00,808
warm Virginia welcome.

3113
02:35:01,602 --> 02:35:03,673
I want you all to know how at home

3114
02:35:03,708 --> 02:35:06,504
I feel here in the Old Dominion.

3115
02:35:06,538 --> 02:35:10,128
And I haven't felt this
way for quite some time.

3116
02:35:10,162 --> 02:35:11,129
Thanks.

3117
02:35:11,163 --> 02:35:13,890
[crowd applaud]

3118
02:35:15,375 --> 02:35:17,377
- That sort of get-up
might go in California,

3119
02:35:17,411 --> 02:35:18,861
but here in Virginia, we have something

3120
02:35:18,895 --> 02:35:20,587
we like to call taste.

3121
02:35:20,621 --> 02:35:22,382
- It doesn't bother John.

3122
02:35:22,416 --> 02:35:24,004
- The more attention that lady gets,

3123
02:35:24,038 --> 02:35:26,524
the closer he is to the senate.

3124
02:35:26,558 --> 02:35:27,663
- We Virginians have to stick together.

3125
02:35:27,697 --> 02:35:29,561
Now I would never
minimize the contribution

3126
02:35:29,596 --> 02:35:32,081
that women have made to this country,

3127
02:35:32,115 --> 02:35:33,703
but we cannot ask the fairer sex

3128
02:35:33,738 --> 02:35:35,947
to go into combat, that is not acceptable

3129
02:35:35,981 --> 02:35:37,569
to most Americans.

3130
02:35:39,122 --> 02:35:40,158
- John.

3131
02:35:40,192 --> 02:35:41,815
- And any so called equal rights amendment

3132
02:35:41,849 --> 02:35:44,231
that would put a woman in harm's way,

3133
02:35:44,265 --> 02:35:46,440
that cannot be condoned.

3134
02:35:47,890 --> 02:35:49,236
[crowd murmurs]

3135
02:35:49,270 --> 02:35:51,411
Women cradle civilization,

3136
02:35:52,481 --> 02:35:54,310
and to ask them to face
the harshest reality

3137
02:35:54,345 --> 02:35:57,865
of modern existence, we can't do that.

3138
02:35:57,900 --> 02:35:58,763
- Oh, boo!

3139
02:36:00,316 --> 02:36:01,904
- What, Elizabeth?

3140
02:36:02,974 --> 02:36:04,355
- Don't women have been
facing the harshest

3141
02:36:04,389 --> 02:36:07,979
realities of life since
the beginning of time?

3142
02:36:08,013 --> 02:36:10,084
I just don't see how you can ...

3143
02:36:10,119 --> 02:36:12,052
- Well I think, and I
see that we will have

3144
02:36:12,086 --> 02:36:14,744
a discussion of foreign policy.

3145
02:36:24,409 --> 02:36:26,687
[munches]

3146
02:36:49,469 --> 02:36:53,438
[celebratory big band music]

3147
02:36:55,440 --> 02:36:58,029
[birds tweet]

3148
02:37:00,445 --> 02:37:02,274
I'll be on the hill til late.

3149
02:37:02,309 --> 02:37:03,966
Stay in Georgetown.

3150
02:37:05,312 --> 02:37:09,420
- I see you want a milk maid
to stay down on the farm.

3151
02:37:10,524 --> 02:37:12,077
- Well you don't wanna
become a Washington wife,

3152
02:37:12,112 --> 02:37:14,252
they all turn ugly.

3153
02:37:14,286 --> 02:37:15,736
- Yeah, and fat.

3154
02:37:17,220 --> 02:37:18,981
- People are talking.

3155
02:37:19,015 --> 02:37:20,465
Making jokes on TV.

3156
02:37:20,500 --> 02:37:23,261
- Oh, why the hell
don't they run the news?

3157
02:37:23,295 --> 02:37:26,540
And not my before and after pictures.

3158
02:37:26,575 --> 02:37:30,026
I didn't marry you sit on the sidelines.

3159
02:37:35,307 --> 02:37:37,896
- Why did you marry me?

3160
02:37:37,931 --> 02:37:39,588
- To be happy.

3161
02:37:39,622 --> 02:37:42,314
But I'm stuck out here
in this chicken coop,

3162
02:37:42,349 --> 02:37:44,006
in paradise, alone!

3163
02:37:46,042 --> 02:37:48,838
[slow sad music]

3164
02:37:55,327 --> 02:37:57,502
[cries]

3165
02:38:13,449 --> 02:38:15,900
[cars pass]

3166
02:38:17,246 --> 02:38:20,560
[police siren blares]

3167
02:38:22,700 --> 02:38:25,565
[knock on door]

3168
02:38:25,599 --> 02:38:28,119
[bird calls]

3169
02:38:29,465 --> 02:38:31,467
- Are we ready?

3170
02:38:31,502 --> 02:38:32,330
- Yes.

3171
02:38:32,364 --> 02:38:33,193
Almost.

3172
02:38:33,227 --> 02:38:34,539
How do I look?

3173
02:38:35,402 --> 02:38:36,714
No response required,

3174
02:38:36,748 --> 02:38:39,717
never putting on that weight again.

3175
02:38:39,751 --> 02:38:41,304
- You look wonderful.

3176
02:38:41,339 --> 02:38:42,858
In fact, if my arthritis permitted,

3177
02:38:42,892 --> 02:38:45,205
I'd do a pirouette myself.

3178
02:38:48,657 --> 02:38:51,660
I see that you've been
medicating your back again.

3179
02:38:51,694 --> 02:38:53,385
- Ah, yes I have.

3180
02:38:53,420 --> 02:38:54,525
- Oh.

3181
02:38:54,559 --> 02:38:58,011
- It hurts me [laughs].

3182
02:38:59,253 --> 02:39:00,565
- You know, it's not the pills,

3183
02:39:00,600 --> 02:39:03,775
it's the cocktail of pills and booze

3184
02:39:05,328 --> 02:39:07,365
that'll kill you.

3185
02:39:07,399 --> 02:39:09,712
- Oh, don't be ridiculous.

3186
02:39:12,197 --> 02:39:13,060
- Yes.

3187
02:39:14,959 --> 02:39:15,822
- Oh well.

3188
02:39:18,721 --> 02:39:21,068
- See you on the boards, love.

3189
02:39:21,103 --> 02:39:22,104
[laughs]

3190
02:39:22,138 --> 02:39:24,727
[crowd cheer]

3191
02:39:30,353 --> 02:39:32,839
- Like a great daff of love.

3192
02:39:32,873 --> 02:39:33,356
- What?

3193
02:39:33,391 --> 02:39:34,668
- This applause.

3194
02:39:34,703 --> 02:39:37,498
Every time, it's like
being loved all over again.

3195
02:39:37,533 --> 02:39:39,086
[laughs]

3196
02:39:39,121 --> 02:39:41,710
[crowd cheer]

3197
02:40:07,356 --> 02:40:09,565
- Elizabeth, do you know who Sally is?

3198
02:40:09,600 --> 02:40:12,050
- Sally, oh yes, of course I know Sally.

3199
02:40:12,085 --> 02:40:13,086
- Hello.

3200
02:40:13,120 --> 02:40:14,259
- Hello Sally.

3201
02:40:15,847 --> 02:40:16,848
So you two have been naughty.

3202
02:40:16,883 --> 02:40:19,195
I understand you went to Las Vegas.

3203
02:40:19,230 --> 02:40:20,024
- Yes.

3204
02:40:20,058 --> 02:40:23,614
For the weekend, and got married.

3205
02:40:23,648 --> 02:40:24,649
- I beg your pardon?

3206
02:40:24,684 --> 02:40:25,823
- Married.

3207
02:40:25,857 --> 02:40:27,134
[laughs]

3208
02:40:27,169 --> 02:40:29,896
- That's strange, I
thought you said married.

3209
02:40:29,930 --> 02:40:30,690
- Yes.

3210
02:40:30,724 --> 02:40:32,450
It's like a great part of love,

3211
02:40:32,484 --> 02:40:36,972
and sometimes we all have
to lower ourselves into it.

3212
02:40:40,423 --> 02:40:41,493
- Well,

3213
02:40:41,528 --> 02:40:42,978
congratulations.

3214
02:40:45,083 --> 02:40:46,567
Richard?

3215
02:40:46,602 --> 02:40:47,776
- Elizabeth.

3216
02:40:48,811 --> 02:40:52,263
[slow emotional music]

3217
02:41:02,998 --> 02:41:05,138
[smashes]

3218
02:41:17,564 --> 02:41:20,187
- Well there you go, she's awake.

3219
02:41:20,222 --> 02:41:21,085
- What?

3220
02:41:22,189 --> 02:41:23,639
- Mom?

3221
02:41:23,674 --> 02:41:25,399
Listen to me.

3222
02:41:25,434 --> 02:41:26,573
You're in trouble.

3223
02:41:26,607 --> 02:41:29,818
You are in very serious trouble.

3224
02:41:29,852 --> 02:41:31,095
- Wait a minute.

3225
02:41:31,992 --> 02:41:35,202
What happened, did I faint or something?

3226
02:41:35,237 --> 02:41:36,203
What happened?

3227
02:41:36,238 --> 02:41:38,309
- It's pills, honey.

3228
02:41:38,343 --> 02:41:39,137
And alcohol.

3229
02:41:40,069 --> 02:41:42,209
You do have a very, very serious problem.

3230
02:41:42,244 --> 02:41:43,003
- That's ridiculous,

3231
02:41:43,038 --> 02:41:44,280
I don't have a problem with alcohol!

3232
02:41:44,315 --> 02:41:45,523
- Listen to me, you are
hurting yourself, mother!

3233
02:41:45,557 --> 02:41:46,524
- I've never had a problem with alcohol!

3234
02:41:46,558 --> 02:41:48,388
- You are hurting yourself!

3235
02:41:48,422 --> 02:41:49,251
- Elizabeth.

3236
02:41:49,285 --> 02:41:51,356
Elizabeth, listen, please!

3237
02:41:51,391 --> 02:41:52,772
You're hurting your family too.

3238
02:41:52,806 --> 02:41:54,325
Do you know that?

3239
02:41:57,500 --> 02:41:58,570
- Am I hurting you?

3240
02:41:58,605 --> 02:41:59,468
- Yes!

3241
02:42:01,090 --> 02:42:01,953
Please.

3242
02:42:06,613 --> 02:42:09,064
[cars pass]

3243
02:42:11,100 --> 02:42:13,516
[birds tweet]

3244
02:42:34,158 --> 02:42:35,262
- Yoohoo, sir?

3245
02:42:38,576 --> 02:42:39,922
- Is there a problem, Miss?

3246
02:42:39,957 --> 02:42:41,372
- Well there's a real problem,

3247
02:42:41,406 --> 02:42:44,168
I don't like the name, Liz.

3248
02:42:44,202 --> 02:42:45,548
- Sorry.

3249
02:42:45,583 --> 02:42:47,965
- And I don't do kitchens.

3250
02:42:49,173 --> 02:42:50,381
- Ma'am,

3251
02:42:50,415 --> 02:42:52,659
this is the Betty Ford Center.

3252
02:42:52,693 --> 02:42:54,868
We do whatever it takes.

3253
02:42:54,903 --> 02:42:58,320
And above all, we don't drink or use.

3254
02:42:58,354 --> 02:42:59,217
Even if--

3255
02:42:59,252 --> 02:43:02,945
- Even if our ass falls off, yes, I know.

3256
02:43:05,430 --> 02:43:08,813
[slow concerned music]

3257
02:43:15,302 --> 02:43:19,065
I'm Elizabeth Taylor and I'm an alcoholic.

3258
02:43:28,488 --> 02:43:31,836
- Thank you all for sharing
your experiences with us.

3259
02:43:31,871 --> 02:43:33,562
Um, Elizabeth.

3260
02:43:34,390 --> 02:43:36,461
Can you recall what event

3261
02:43:36,496 --> 02:43:39,740
or incident it was that caused you

3262
02:43:39,775 --> 02:43:41,501
to recognize the fact that

3263
02:43:41,535 --> 02:43:43,123
you had a problem?

3264
02:43:46,955 --> 02:43:48,542
- I still have a hard time believing

3265
02:43:48,577 --> 02:43:51,200
I'm actually here [laughs].

3266
02:43:51,235 --> 02:43:52,167
But yes ...

3267
02:43:53,720 --> 02:43:56,033
[sighs]

3268
02:43:56,067 --> 02:43:59,036
I remember waking up in hospital,

3269
02:44:00,037 --> 02:44:02,798
surrounded by friends and family,

3270
02:44:02,833 --> 02:44:05,939
and they said that I had a problem.

3271
02:44:07,561 --> 02:44:09,080
- We all have a problem,

3272
02:44:09,115 --> 02:44:11,117
that's why we're here.

3273
02:44:12,152 --> 02:44:13,602
- Well I guess I'd become an alcoholic,

3274
02:44:13,636 --> 02:44:17,399
and that combined with the
pain killers I was taking,

3275
02:44:17,433 --> 02:44:19,228
I couldn't handle it.

3276
02:44:21,230 --> 02:44:23,060
- At least you didn't try to hide it.

3277
02:44:23,094 --> 02:44:25,614
You had the courage to
come out in the open.

3278
02:44:25,648 --> 02:44:27,133
- Well ...

3279
02:44:27,167 --> 02:44:31,689
Yes, I just hope to God
that's all behind me now.

3280
02:44:31,723 --> 02:44:35,175
[slow optimistic music]

3281
02:44:37,522 --> 02:44:41,250
- That woman doesn't have one
single unexpressed thought

3282
02:44:41,285 --> 02:44:42,251
in her head.

3283
02:44:48,119 --> 02:44:50,190
[laughs]

3284
02:45:06,172 --> 02:45:09,485
No longer mourn for me when I am dead,

3285
02:45:10,555 --> 02:45:14,387
than you shall hear
the surly, sullen bell.

3286
02:45:15,526 --> 02:45:17,735
Give warning to the world

3287
02:45:17,769 --> 02:45:20,945
that I am fled from this vile world,

3288
02:45:24,052 --> 02:45:27,227
with vilest worlds to dwell.

3289
02:45:27,262 --> 02:45:28,539
[men shout]

3290
02:45:28,573 --> 02:45:29,885
- Miss Taylor!

3291
02:45:29,920 --> 02:45:31,335
- Madam!

3292
02:45:31,369 --> 02:45:34,096
[cameras click]

3293
02:45:37,237 --> 02:45:40,240
- One photograph, just one!

3294
02:45:40,275 --> 02:45:43,968
[speaks in foreign language]

3295
02:45:44,003 --> 02:45:46,626
- I love you, Richard.

3296
02:45:46,660 --> 02:45:49,525
And I will never cease loving you.

3297
02:45:57,257 --> 02:45:58,120
Hey, Rock.

3298
02:45:58,879 --> 02:46:01,468
[laughs]

3299
02:46:01,503 --> 02:46:02,469
- Hi Bessy.

3300
02:46:02,504 --> 02:46:04,161
Careful who you kiss.

3301
02:46:04,195 --> 02:46:06,680
- I always kiss gorgeous men.

3302
02:46:06,715 --> 02:46:08,544
- Not so gorgeous.

3303
02:46:08,579 --> 02:46:09,545
Not no more.

3304
02:46:09,580 --> 02:46:10,857
- Oh baloney.

3305
02:46:10,891 --> 02:46:13,308
- Not like you, you piss me off.

3306
02:46:13,342 --> 02:46:15,586
You look as good as you
did when we made Giant.

3307
02:46:15,620 --> 02:46:17,829
- Oh, boy, are you some actor.

3308
02:46:17,864 --> 02:46:19,383
Who wrote your lines, hmm?

3309
02:46:19,417 --> 02:46:20,901
- Nah.

3310
02:46:20,936 --> 02:46:21,937
I'm serious.

3311
02:46:21,972 --> 02:46:23,594
You look great.

3312
02:46:23,628 --> 02:46:25,423
[coughs]

3313
02:46:25,458 --> 02:46:26,873
How's your life?

3314
02:46:26,907 --> 02:46:28,979
- Oh, you know me, kiddo.

3315
02:46:29,013 --> 02:46:31,084
I'm a survivor, it's in the genes.

3316
02:46:31,119 --> 02:46:33,362
- You always did look hot in your jeans.

3317
02:46:33,397 --> 02:46:35,468
[laughs]

3318
02:46:38,747 --> 02:46:40,507
- Hey partner.

3319
02:46:40,542 --> 02:46:44,097
What do you say we head
on back to Texas, hmm?

3320
02:46:44,132 --> 02:46:46,203
- I'd like to go back.

3321
02:46:46,237 --> 02:46:49,275
[slow concerned music]

3322
02:46:49,309 --> 02:46:50,172
Anywhere.

3323
02:46:52,623 --> 02:46:53,486
- I know.

3324
02:47:00,148 --> 02:47:03,254
- You know what I miss about Texas?

3325
02:47:04,566 --> 02:47:06,223
Chocolate Martinis.

3326
02:47:07,258 --> 02:47:09,674
[laughs]

3327
02:47:09,709 --> 02:47:11,366
- Okay, then I'll give you one.

3328
02:47:11,400 --> 02:47:12,367
- Just one.

3329
02:47:12,401 --> 02:47:13,506
- A whole batch.

3330
02:47:13,540 --> 02:47:16,129
[birds tweet]

3331
02:47:21,583 --> 02:47:23,378
- Chocolate Martinis.

3332
02:47:34,458 --> 02:47:37,185
- I am tired and I am grieving.

3333
02:47:38,427 --> 02:47:41,775
I am tired of us having to
convince the world out there

3334
02:47:41,810 --> 02:47:45,952
that AIDS is a universal
threat to all mankind.

3335
02:47:45,986 --> 02:47:49,128
[crowd applaud]

3336
02:47:49,162 --> 02:47:51,095
I have held a good friend in my arms

3337
02:47:51,130 --> 02:47:53,408
as his body began to fail,

3338
02:47:53,442 --> 02:47:56,445
and I am compelled by grief.

3339
02:47:56,480 --> 02:47:58,723
[cameras click]

3340
02:47:58,758 --> 02:48:01,209
The delays in confronting AIDS

3341
02:48:01,243 --> 02:48:03,970
tragically remind me of
the high price to be paid

3342
02:48:04,004 --> 02:48:06,179
when prejudice prevails.

3343
02:48:07,905 --> 02:48:12,289
AIDS has taught me how
fragile human existence is,

3344
02:48:12,323 --> 02:48:15,085
and that every life is to be cherished.

3345
02:48:15,119 --> 02:48:17,294
[crowd applaud]

3346
02:48:17,328 --> 02:48:18,812
- Are you gonna act again, Miss Taylor,

3347
02:48:18,847 --> 02:48:20,814
or are you just gonna
pursue this AIDS work?

3348
02:48:20,849 --> 02:48:22,368
- I don't know if I pursue
it or it pursues me,

3349
02:48:22,402 --> 02:48:23,507
but--

3350
02:48:23,541 --> 02:48:24,680
- Miss Taylor?

3351
02:48:26,717 --> 02:48:27,821
- Since Rock Hudson's death,

3352
02:48:27,856 --> 02:48:29,892
I guess it's made the
work a little easier.

3353
02:48:29,927 --> 02:48:32,274
- Yes, but I'll tell you what amazes me.

3354
02:48:32,309 --> 02:48:33,758
It's truly amazing,

3355
02:48:33,793 --> 02:48:35,829
I call good friends of mine

3356
02:48:35,864 --> 02:48:37,555
to ask them to be a part of this,

3357
02:48:37,590 --> 02:48:38,832
lifelong friends,

3358
02:48:38,867 --> 02:48:41,973
and they duck out on me, they
just don't return my calls.

3359
02:48:42,008 --> 02:48:43,216
- Well, you know, it's AIDS.

3360
02:48:43,251 --> 02:48:44,700
People are embarrassed.

3361
02:48:44,735 --> 02:48:46,046
- Yes, but that's terrible,

3362
02:48:46,081 --> 02:48:47,462
I mean, it's like alcoholism,

3363
02:48:47,496 --> 02:48:50,982
it shouldn't be a disease
of shame, and it is.

3364
02:48:51,017 --> 02:48:51,983
- Well, what can you do?

3365
02:48:52,018 --> 02:48:54,365
- Well, we can all do something.

3366
02:48:54,400 --> 02:48:55,366
Try to make people aware,

3367
02:48:55,401 --> 02:48:56,367
I believe that's the first step,

3368
02:48:56,402 --> 02:48:57,989
that's what I'm trying to do.

3369
02:48:58,024 --> 02:48:58,956
Thank you.

3370
02:48:58,990 --> 02:48:59,819
- Over here, Miss Taylor, over here.

3371
02:48:59,853 --> 02:49:00,820
- Miss Taylor?

3372
02:49:00,854 --> 02:49:01,855
- One more question.

3373
02:49:01,890 --> 02:49:03,788
[pours]

3374
02:49:03,823 --> 02:49:04,686
- Uhuh.

3375
02:49:05,652 --> 02:49:09,139
No, she's handling the press pretty well.

3376
02:49:09,173 --> 02:49:10,209
Right?

3377
02:49:11,244 --> 02:49:12,211
[plane takes off]

3378
02:49:12,245 --> 02:49:15,214
Well, we arrived at 2:30 LA time.

3379
02:49:17,285 --> 02:49:20,564
I'm afraid she's gonna have
to see a doctor though.

3380
02:49:20,598 --> 02:49:21,461
Yeah.

3381
02:49:24,119 --> 02:49:25,845
Yeah, I'm afraid so.

3382
02:49:28,572 --> 02:49:29,435
Mhmm.

3383
02:49:32,300 --> 02:49:34,129
- I don't know what
got me back here, I ...

3384
02:49:34,164 --> 02:49:37,615
I don't know, I'm trying to booze, food.

3385
02:49:41,343 --> 02:49:42,827
Pills, again.

3386
02:49:42,862 --> 02:49:43,897
- Yeah.

3387
02:49:43,932 --> 02:49:45,865
- It's always the pills for me too.

3388
02:49:45,899 --> 02:49:47,522
- Yes, but these were prescription.

3389
02:49:47,556 --> 02:49:48,419
- Yeah.

3390
02:49:48,454 --> 02:49:50,076
- They were prescribed to me for my back.

3391
02:49:50,110 --> 02:49:53,079
Damarall, percoden, valium.

3392
02:49:53,113 --> 02:49:54,598
- All in one day?

3393
02:49:55,392 --> 02:49:56,841
- Give me the name of that doctor.

3394
02:49:56,876 --> 02:49:59,016
[laughs]

3395
02:49:59,050 --> 02:50:01,639
- Oh honey, you're just like me.

3396
02:50:01,674 --> 02:50:03,123
- I beg your pardon?

3397
02:50:03,158 --> 02:50:06,196
- Give me pills, booze, food, men.

3398
02:50:07,852 --> 02:50:09,716
Nothing's ever enough.

3399
02:50:11,131 --> 02:50:12,443
- Yes, but you don't equate

3400
02:50:12,478 --> 02:50:14,859
alcohol and pills with men?

3401
02:50:16,136 --> 02:50:18,794
- Yes, it's a love addiction.

3402
02:50:18,829 --> 02:50:20,796
Look at me, I've been married four times,

3403
02:50:20,831 --> 02:50:23,523
and I never found anything,

3404
02:50:23,558 --> 02:50:25,042
not in this lifetime to fill up

3405
02:50:25,076 --> 02:50:27,803
that great big emptiness inside.

3406
02:50:29,322 --> 02:50:30,496
- Oh my God,

3407
02:50:30,530 --> 02:50:34,362
I've never thought of
love as an addiction.

3408
02:50:35,328 --> 02:50:37,572
So your name's Larry?

3409
02:50:37,606 --> 02:50:38,573
- Yeah.

3410
02:50:38,607 --> 02:50:39,436
Larry Vercinski.

3411
02:50:39,470 --> 02:50:40,333
- Hmm.

3412
02:50:41,886 --> 02:50:43,612
And what do you, Larry?

3413
02:50:43,647 --> 02:50:44,717
[ducks quack]

3414
02:50:44,751 --> 02:50:46,097
- I move earth.

3415
02:50:46,132 --> 02:50:48,721
[laughs]

3416
02:50:48,755 --> 02:50:49,756
- I'll bet.

3417
02:50:49,791 --> 02:50:51,310
[laughs]

3418
02:50:51,344 --> 02:50:53,243
- Operator, moving equipment.

3419
02:50:53,277 --> 02:50:55,003
- Ah, I'm impressed.

3420
02:50:58,524 --> 02:51:00,422
- Do you wanna walk?

3421
02:51:01,734 --> 02:51:02,597
- Okay.

3422
02:51:04,392 --> 02:51:06,428
I'm a bit slow at the start.

3423
02:51:06,463 --> 02:51:08,741
[clears throat]

3424
02:51:08,775 --> 02:51:12,331
Maybe I should get a job
moving earth [laughs].

3425
02:51:12,365 --> 02:51:14,988
God knows I need something.

3426
02:51:15,023 --> 02:51:17,474
My career, ugh, almost dead.

3427
02:51:19,165 --> 02:51:21,719
- But you're Elizabeth Taylor.

3428
02:51:21,754 --> 02:51:23,100
- Being Elizabeth Taylor used to be

3429
02:51:23,134 --> 02:51:25,516
good and sufficient reason
for waking up every morning.

3430
02:51:25,551 --> 02:51:28,070
Now it just seems so nothing.

3431
02:51:29,279 --> 02:51:31,867
- Oh come on, don't talk like that.

3432
02:51:31,902 --> 02:51:33,075
You're still full of fire,

3433
02:51:33,110 --> 02:51:35,940
you have your AIDS charity.

3434
02:51:35,975 --> 02:51:36,941
How many people that matter

3435
02:51:36,976 --> 02:51:39,634
care about people like you do?

3436
02:51:39,668 --> 02:51:42,982
Even that's bigger than
being Elizabeth Taylor, huh?

3437
02:51:43,016 --> 02:51:44,121
No offense.

3438
02:51:44,155 --> 02:51:45,225
[laughs]

3439
02:51:45,260 --> 02:51:47,952
- It's okay, kid, I can take it.

3440
02:51:49,644 --> 02:51:52,888
Someone suggested I start a new career.

3441
02:51:52,923 --> 02:51:53,889
In perfume.

3442
02:51:53,924 --> 02:51:55,166
- There you go.

3443
02:51:55,201 --> 02:51:56,961
What would you call it?

3444
02:51:56,996 --> 02:51:58,515
- Hmm.

3445
02:51:58,549 --> 02:52:00,448
What do I know best?

3446
02:52:01,276 --> 02:52:02,691
- What?

3447
02:52:02,726 --> 02:52:03,727
- Passion.

3448
02:52:03,761 --> 02:52:04,900
[laughs]

3449
02:52:04,935 --> 02:52:07,869
[happy rock music]

3450
02:52:23,988 --> 02:52:24,955
- John.

3451
02:52:24,989 --> 02:52:25,956
Just walk in.

3452
02:52:25,990 --> 02:52:27,095
- This is it.

3453
02:52:27,129 --> 02:52:27,958
- Wow.

3454
02:52:27,992 --> 02:52:28,821
[laughs]

3455
02:52:28,855 --> 02:52:30,961
[till dings]

3456
02:52:30,995 --> 02:52:32,963
[laughs]

3457
02:52:32,997 --> 02:52:36,449
[sexy country music]

3458
02:52:36,484 --> 02:52:38,313
- That is a double-decker.

3459
02:52:38,348 --> 02:52:40,453
Pickles, onions, relish, mustard

3460
02:52:40,488 --> 02:52:42,282
and mayonnaise with fries.

3461
02:52:42,317 --> 02:52:43,283
You got enough fries?

3462
02:52:43,318 --> 02:52:44,354
- Oh yes.

3463
02:52:45,803 --> 02:52:49,013
Of course I haven't been to
a place like this in years.

3464
02:52:49,048 --> 02:52:50,394
- Right well,

3465
02:52:50,429 --> 02:52:54,225
it's not exactly the typical
beller palace, but ...

3466
02:52:54,260 --> 02:52:55,572
Ready to leap?

3467
02:52:56,849 --> 02:52:57,815
- Mmm.

3468
02:52:57,850 --> 02:52:59,127
Yes, let's leap.

3469
02:53:09,171 --> 02:53:10,932
[laugh]

3470
02:53:10,966 --> 02:53:12,416
What?

3471
02:53:12,451 --> 02:53:15,937
- I've never met anyone like you before.

3472
02:53:15,971 --> 02:53:17,352
It's scary.

3473
02:53:17,387 --> 02:53:18,698
It's wonderful.

3474
02:53:19,458 --> 02:53:22,322
- Well, it could be dangerous.

3475
02:53:22,357 --> 02:53:24,532
What if we fall in love?

3476
02:53:28,156 --> 02:53:30,400
- I think I already have.

3477
02:53:35,335 --> 02:53:38,511
[cheer and applaud]

3478
02:53:44,897 --> 02:53:48,107
[birds tweet]

3479
02:53:48,141 --> 02:53:50,799
[truck drives]

3480
02:53:55,597 --> 02:53:58,393
[water trickles]

3481
02:53:58,428 --> 02:54:00,878
[cat meows]

3482
02:54:02,949 --> 02:54:04,951
[sighs]

3483
02:54:07,575 --> 02:54:09,680
- How's my little girl?

3484
02:54:10,474 --> 02:54:12,165
- Happy.

3485
02:54:12,200 --> 02:54:14,167
And about to be 60.

